# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: embedded-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This may be done by hardware or firmware in the CPU, or by a separate processor in the computer system.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] On some systems, a power-on reset (POR) does not initiate booting, and the operator must initiate booting after POR completes.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] IBM uses the term **Initial Program Load** (**IPL**) on some product lines.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Restarting a computer is also called *rebooting*, which can be "hard", e.g., after electrical power to the CPU is switched from off to on, or "soft", where the power is not cut.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] On some systems, a soft boot may optionally clear RAM to zero.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Both hard and soft booting can be initiated by hardware, such as a button press, or by a software command.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Booting is complete when the operative runtime system, typically the operating system and some applications, is attained.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The process of returning a computer from a state of sleep (suspension) does not involve booting; however, restoring it from a state of hibernation does.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Minimally, some embedded systems do not require a noticeable boot sequence to begin functioning, and when turned on, may simply run operational programs that are stored in read-only memory (ROM).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] All computing systems are state machines, and a reboot may be the only method to return to a designated zero-state from an unintended, locked state.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In addition to loading an operating system or stand-alone utility, the boot process can also load a storage dump program for diagnosing problems in an operating system.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The earliest known recorded use of "boot" as the shortened form for "bootstrap" is 1975.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] There are many different methods available to load a short initial program into a computer.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] These methods range from simple, physical input to removable media that can hold more complex programs.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Early computers in the 1940s and 1950s were one-of-a-kind engineering efforts that could take weeks to program, and program loading was one of many problems that had to be solved.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] An early computer, ENIAC, had no program stored in memory but was set up for each problem by a configuration of interconnecting cables.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Bootstrapping did not apply to ENIAC, whose hardware configuration was ready for solving problems as soon as power was applied.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The EDSAC system, the second stored-program computer to be built, used stepping switches to transfer a fixed program into memory when its start button was pressed.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The program stored on this device, which David Wheeler completed in late 1948, loaded further instructions from punched tape and then executed them.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The first programmable computers for commercial sale, such as the UNIVAC I and the IBM 701 included features to make their operation simpler.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] They typically included instructions that performed a complete input or output operation.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The same hardware logic could be used to load the contents of a punch card (the most typical ones) or other input media, such as a magnetic drum or magnetic tape, that contained a bootstrap program by pressing a single button.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This booting concept was called a variety of names for IBM computers of the 1950s and early 1960s, but IBM used the term "Initial Program Load" with the IBM 7030 Stretch and later used it for their mainframe lines, starting with the System/360 in 1964.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The IBM 701 computer (1952–1956) had a "Load" button that initiated reading of the first 36-bit word into main memory from a punched card in a card reader, a magnetic tape in a tape drive, or a magnetic drum unit, depending on the position of the Load Selector switch.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The left 18-bit half-word was then executed as an instruction, which usually read additional words into memory.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The loaded boot program was then executed, which, in turn, loaded a larger program from that medium into memory without further help from the human operator.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The IBM 704, IBM 7090, and IBM 7094 had similar mechanisms, but with different load buttons for different devices.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The term "boot" has been used in this sense since at least 1958.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Other IBM computers of that era had similar features.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] For example, the IBM 1401 system (1959) used a card reader to load a program from a punched card.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The 80 characters stored in the punched card were read into memory locations 001 to 080, then the computer would branch to memory location 001 to read its first stored instruction.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This instruction was always the same: move the information in these first 80 memory locations to an assembly area where the information in punched cards 2, 3, 4, and so on, could be combined to form the stored program.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Once this information was moved to the assembly area, the machine would branch to an instruction in location 080 (read a card) and the next card would be read and its information processed.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Another example was the IBM 650 (1953), a decimal machine, which had a group of ten 10-position switches on its operator panel that were addressable as a memory word (address 8000) and could be executed as an instruction.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Thus, setting the switches to 7004000400 and pressing the appropriate button would read the first card in the card reader into memory (op code 70), starting at address 400 and then jump to 400 to begin executing the program on that card.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] IBM's competitors also offered single-button program load.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] A noteworthy variation of this is found on the Burroughs B1700, where there is neither a boot ROM nor a hardwired IPL operation.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Instead, after the system is reset, it reads and executes microinstructions sequentially from a cassette tape drive mounted on the front panel; this sets up a boot loader in RAM, which is then executed.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] However, since this makes few assumptions about the system it can equally well be used to load diagnostic (Maintenance Test Routine) tapes which display an intelligible code on the front panel even in cases of gross CPU failure.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In the IBM System/360 and its successors, including the current z/Architecture machines, the boot process is known as *Initial Program Load* (IPL).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] IBM coined this term for the 7030 (Stretch), revived it for the design of the System/360, and continues to use it in those environments today.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In the System/360 processors, an IPL is initiated by the computer operator by selecting the three hexadecimal digit device address (CUU; C=I/O Channel address, UU=Control unit and Device address) followed by pressing the *LOAD* button.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] On the high end System/360 models, most System/370 and some later systems, the functions of the switches and the LOAD button are simulated using selectable areas on the screen of a graphics console, often an IBM 2250-like device or an IBM 3270-like device.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] For example, on the System/370 Model 158, the keyboard sequence 0-7-X (zero, seven and X, in that order) results in an IPL from the device address that was keyed into the input area.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The Amdahl 470V/6 and related CPUs supported four hexadecimal digits on those CPUs that had the optional second channel unit installed, for a total of 32 channels.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Later, IBM would also support more than 16 channels.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The IPL function in the System/360 and its successors prior to IBM Z, and its compatibles, such as Amdahl's, reads 24 bytes from an operator-specified device into main storage starting at real address zero.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The second and third groups of eight bytes are treated as Channel Command Words (CCWs) to continue loading the startup program (the first CCW is always simulated by the CPU and consists of a Read IPL command, 02h, with command chaining and suppress incorrect length indication being enforced).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] When the I/O channel commands are complete, the first group of eight bytes is then loaded into the processor's Program Status Word (PSW) and the startup program begins execution at the location designated by that PSW.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] IBM introduced some evolutionary changes in the IPL process, changing some details for System/370 Extended Architecture (S/370-XA) and later, and adding a new type of IPL for z/Architecture.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Minicomputers, starting with the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-5 and PDP-8 (1965) simplified design by using the CPU to assist input and output operations.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This saved cost but made booting more complicated than pressing a single button.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Minicomputers typically had some way to *toggle in* short programs by manipulating an array of switches on the front panel.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Since the early minicomputers used magnetic-core memory, which did not lose its information when power was off, these bootstrap loaders would remain in place unless they were erased.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Erasure sometimes happened accidentally when a program bug caused a loop that overwrote all of memory.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Other minicomputers with such simple form of booting include Hewlett-Packard's HP 2100 series (mid-1960s), the original Data General Nova (1969), and DEC's PDP-4 (1962) and PDP-11 (1970).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] As the I/O operations needed to cause a read operation on a minicomputer I/O device were typically different for different device controllers, different bootstrap programs were needed for different devices.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] DEC later added, in 1971, an optional diode matrix read-only memory for the PDP-11 that stored a bootstrap program of up to 32 words (64 bytes).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] It consisted of a printed circuit card, the M792, that plugged into the Unibus and held a 32 by 16 array of semiconductor diodes.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] With all 512 diodes in place, the memory contained all "one" bits; the card was programmed by cutting off each diode whose bit was to be "zero".
[src:embedded-systems/booting] DEC also sold versions of the card, the BM792-Yx series, pre-programmed for many standard input devices by simply omitting the unneeded diodes.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Following the older approach, the earlier PDP-1 has a hardware loader, such that an operator needs only push the *load* switch to instruct the paper tape reader to load a program directly into core memory.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The PDP-7, PDP-9, and PDP-15 successors to the PDP-4 have an added Read-In button to read a program in from paper tape and jump to it.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The Data General Supernova used front panel switches to cause the computer to automatically load instructions into memory from a device specified by the front panel's data switches, and then jump to loaded code.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In a minicomputer with a paper tape reader, the first program to run in the boot process, the boot loader, would read into core memory either the second-stage boot loader (often called a *Binary Loader*) that could read paper tape with checksum or the operating system from an outside storage medium.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] A related example is based on a loader for a Nicolet Instrument Corporation minicomputer of the 1970s, using the paper tape reader-punch unit on a Teletype Model 33 ASR teleprinter.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The bytes of its second-stage loader are read from paper tape in reverse order.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The length of the second stage loader is such that the final byte overwrites location 7.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] After the instruction in location 6 executes, location 7 starts the second stage loader executing.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The second stage loader then waits for the much longer tape containing the operating system to be placed in the tape reader.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The difference between the boot loader and second stage loader is the addition of checking code to trap paper tape read errors, a frequent occurrence with relatively low-cost, "part-time-duty" hardware, such as the Teletype Model 33 ASR.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The earliest microcomputers, such as the Altair 8800 (released first in 1975) and an even earlier, similar machine (based on the Intel 8008 CPU) had no bootstrapping hardware as such.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] When powered up, the CPU would see memory that would contain random data.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The front panels of these machines carried toggle switches for entering addresses and data, one switch per bit of the computer memory word and address bus.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Simple additions to the hardware permitted one memory location at a time to be loaded from those switches to store bootstrap code.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Meanwhile, the CPU was kept from attempting to execute memory content.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Once correctly loaded, the CPU was enabled to execute the bootstrapping code.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This process, similar to that used for several earlier minicomputers, was tedious and had to be error-free.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The introduction of integrated circuit read-only memory (ROM), with its many variants, including mask-programmed ROMs, programmable ROMs (PROM), erasable programmable ROMs (EPROM), and flash memory, reduced the physical size and cost of ROM.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This allowed firmware boot programs to be included as part of the computer.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The Data General Nova 1200 (1970) and Nova 800 (1971) had a program load switch that, in combination with options that provided two ROM chips, loaded a program into main memory from those ROM chips and jumped to it.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Digital Equipment Corporation introduced the integrated-circuit-ROM-based BM873 (1974), M9301 (1977), M9312 (1978), REV11-A and REV11-C, MRV11-C, and MRV11-D ROM memories, all usable as bootstrap ROMs.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] An Italian telephone switching computer, called "Gruppi Speciali", patented in 1975 by Alberto Ciaramella, a researcher at CSELT, included an (external) ROM.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Gruppi Speciali was, starting from 1975, a fully single-button machine booting into the operating system from a ROM memory composed of semiconductors, not ferrite cores.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Although the ROM device was not natively embedded in the computer of Gruppi Speciali, due to the design of the machine, it also allowed the single-button ROM booting in machines not designed for that (therefore, this "bootstrap device" was architecture-independent), e.g., the PDP-11.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Storing the state of the machine after the switch-off was also in place, which was another critical feature in the telephone switching contest.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some minicomputers and superminicomputers include a separate console processor that bootstraps the main processor.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The PDP-11/44 had an Intel 8085 as a console processor; the VAX-11/780, the first member of Digital's VAX line of 32-bit superminicomputers, had an LSI-11-based console processor, and the VAX-11/730 had an 8085-based console processor.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] These console processors could boot the main processor from various storage devices.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some other superminicomputers, such as the VAX-11/750, implement console functions, including the first stage of booting, in CPU microcode.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] A system built using that microprocessor will have the permanent ROM occupying these special locations so that the system always begins operating without operator assistance.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] For example, Intel x86 processors always start by running the instructions beginning at F000:FFF0, while for the MOS 6502 processor, initialization begins by reading a two-byte vector address at $FFFD (MS byte) and $FFFC (LS byte) and jumping to that location to run the bootstrap code.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Apple Computer's first computer, the Apple 1, introduced in 1976, featured PROM chips that eliminated the need for a front panel for the boot process (as was the case with the Altair 8800) in a commercial computer.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Due to the expense of read-only memory at the time, the Apple II booted its disk operating systems using a series of very small incremental steps, each passing control onward to the next phase of the gradually more complex boot process.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Because so little of the disk operating system relied on ROM, the hardware was also extremely flexible and supported a wide range of customized disk copy protection mechanisms.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some operating systems, most notably pre-1995 Macintosh systems from Apple, are so closely interwoven with their hardware that it is impossible to natively boot an operating system other than the standard one.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This is the opposite extreme of the scenario using switches mentioned above; it is highly inflexible but relatively error-proof and foolproof as long as all hardware is working normally.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] A common solution in such situations is to design a boot loader that works as a program belonging to the standard OS that hijacks the system and loads the alternative OS.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This technique was used by Apple for its A/UX Unix implementation and copied by various freeware operating systems and BeOS Personal Edition 5.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some machines, like the Atari ST microcomputer, were "instant-on", with the operating system executing from a ROM.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Retrieval of the OS from secondary or tertiary store was thus eliminated as one of the characteristic operations for bootstrapping.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] To allow system customizations, accessories, and other support software to be loaded automatically, the Atari's floppy drive was read for additional components during the boot process.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] There was a timeout delay that provided time to manually insert a floppy as the system searched for the extra components.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This could be avoided by inserting a blank disk.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The IBM Personal Computer included ROM-based firmware called the BIOS; one of the functions of that firmware was to perform a power-on self test when the machine was powered up, and then to read software from a boot device and execute it.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Firmware compatible with the BIOS on the IBM Personal Computer is used in IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The UEFI was developed by Intel, originally for Itanium-based machines, and later also used as an alternative to the BIOS in x86-based machines, including Apple Macs using Intel processors.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Unix workstations originally had vendor-specific ROM-based firmware.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Sun Microsystems later developed OpenBoot, later known as Open Firmware, which incorporated a Forth interpreter, with much of the firmware being written in Forth.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] It was standardized by the IEEE as IEEE standard 1275-1994; firmware that implements that standard was used in PowerPC-based Macs and some other PowerPC-based machines, as well as Sun's own SPARC-based computers.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The Advanced RISC Computing specification defined another firmware standard, which was implemented on some MIPS-based and Alpha-based machines and the SGI Visual Workstation x86-based workstations.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] When a computer is turned off, its software‍—‌including operating systems, application code, and data‍—‌remains stored on non-volatile memory.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] When the computer is powered on, it typically does not have an operating system or its loader in random-access memory (RAM).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The small program that starts this sequence is known as a *bootstrap loader*, *bootstrap* or *boot loader*.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Often, multiple-stage boot loaders are used, during which several programs of increasing complexity load one after the other in a process of chain loading.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some earlier computer systems, upon receiving a boot signal from a human operator or a peripheral device, may load a very small number of fixed instructions into memory at a specific location, initialize at least one CPU, and then point the CPU to the instructions and start their execution.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] These instructions typically start an input operation from some peripheral device (which may be switch-selectable by the operator).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Smaller computers often use less flexible but more automatic boot loader mechanisms to ensure that the computer starts quickly and with a predetermined software configuration.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In many desktop computers, for example, the bootstrapping process begins with the CPU executing software contained in ROM (for example, the BIOS of an IBM PC) at a predefined address (some CPUs, including the Intel x86 series are designed to execute this software after reset without outside help).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This software contains rudimentary functionality to search for devices eligible to participate in booting, and load a small program from a special section (most commonly the boot sector) of the most promising device, typically starting at a fixed entry point such as the start of the sector.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] On systems with those constraints, the first program loaded into RAM may not be sufficiently large to load the operating system and, instead, must load another, larger program.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The first program loaded into RAM is called a first-stage boot loader, and the program it loads is called a second-stage boot loader.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] On many embedded CPUs, the CPU built-in boot ROM, sometimes called the zero-stage boot loader, can find and load first-stage boot loaders.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Examples of first-stage (hardware initialization stage) boot loaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot and Das U-Boot.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] On the IBM PC, the boot loader in the Master Boot Record (MBR) and the Partition Boot Record (PBR) was coded to require at least 32 KB (later expanded to 64 KB) of system memory and only use instructions supported by the original 8088/8086 processors.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, UEFI or Open Firmware, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Many boot loaders (like GNU GRUB, rEFInd, Windows's BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and Windows NT/2000/XP's NTLDR) can be configured to give the user multiple booting choices.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some boot loaders can also load other boot loaders; for example, GRUB loads BOOTMGR instead of loading Windows directly.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Usually, a default choice is preselected with a time delay during which a user can press a key to change the choice; after this delay, the default choice is automatically run so normal booting can occur without interaction.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The boot process can be considered complete when the computer is ready to interact with the user, or the operating system is capable of running system programs or application programs.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some boot loaders, such as Das U-Boot and iBoot, include both first- and second-stage boot functions.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Many embedded systems must boot immediately.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] For example, waiting a minute for a digital television or a GPS navigation device to start is generally unacceptable.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Therefore, such devices have software systems in ROM or flash memory so the device can begin functioning immediately; little or no loading is necessary, because the loading can be precomputed and stored on the ROM when the device is made.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Large and complex systems may have boot procedures that proceed in multiple phases until finally the operating system and other programs are loaded and ready to execute.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Because operating systems are designed as if they never start or stop, a boot loader might load the operating system, configure itself as a mere process within that system, and then irrevocably transfer control to the operating system.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The boot loader then terminates normally as any other process would.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Most computers are also capable of booting over a computer network.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In this scenario, the operating system is stored on the disk of a server, and certain parts of it are transferred to the client using a simple protocol such as the Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over control of the booting process.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] As with the second-stage boot loader, network booting begins by using generic network access methods provided by the network interface's boot ROM, which typically contains a Preboot Execution Environment (PXE) image.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] No drivers are required, but the system functionality is limited until the operating system kernel and drivers are transferred and started.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] As a result, once the ROM-based booting has completed it is entirely possible to network boot into an operating system that itself does not have the ability to use the network interface.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The boot device is the storage device from which the operating system is loaded.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Older, less common BIOS-bootable devices include floppy disk drives, Zip drives, and LS-120 drives.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] IBM-compatible PCs are examples that use horizontal integrated hardware and UEFI/BIOS firmware.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Typically, the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS) will allow the user to configure a *boot order*.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] If the boot order is set to "first, the DVD drive; second, the hard disk drive", then the firmware will try to boot from the DVD drive, and if this fails (e.g., because there is no DVD in the drive), it will try to boot from the local hard disk drive.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] For example, on a PC with Windows installed on the hard drive, the user could set the boot order to the one given above, and then insert a Linux Live CD in order to try out Linux without having to install an operating system onto the hard drive.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This is an example of dual booting, in which the user chooses which operating system to start after the computer has performed its power-on self-test (POST).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Several devices are available that enable the user to *quick-boot* into what is usually a variant of Linux for various simple tasks such as Internet access; examples are Splashtop and Latitude ON.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This memory location typically contains a jump instruction that transfers execution to the location of the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) start-up program.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This program runs a power-on self-test (POST) to check and initialize required devices such as main memory (DRAM), the PCI bus and the PCI devices (including running embedded option ROMs).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] One of the most involved steps is setting up DRAM over SPD, further complicated by the fact that, at this point, memory is very limited.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] After initializing required hardware, the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) goes through a pre-configured list of non-volatile storage devices ("boot device sequence") until it finds one that is bootable.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Once the BIOS has found a bootable device it loads the boot sector to linear address 7C00h (usually segment:offset 0000h:7C00h, but some BIOSes erroneously use 07C0h:0000h) and transfers execution to the boot code.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In the case of a hard disk, this is referred to as the Master Boot Record (MBR).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The conventional MBR code checks the MBR's partition table for a partition set as *bootable* (the one with *active* flag set).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] If an active partition is found, the MBR code loads the boot sector code from that partition, known as Volume Boot Record (VBR), and executes it.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The MBR boot code is often operating-system specific.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The boot sector code is the first-stage boot loader.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The boot loader was then able to load the first three sectors of the file into memory, which happened to contain another embedded boot loader able to load the remainder of the file into memory.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] When Microsoft added LBA and FAT32 support, they even switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors and using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file system, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The VBR is often OS-specific; however, its main function is to load and execute the operating system boot loader file (such as `bootmgr` or `ntldr`), which is the second-stage boot loader, from an active partition.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Then the boot loader loads the OS kernel from the storage device.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] If there is no active partition, or the active partition's boot sector is invalid, the MBR may load a secondary boot loader which will select a partition (often via user input) and load its boot sector, which usually loads the corresponding operating system kernel.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In some cases, the MBR may also attempt to load secondary boot loaders before trying to boot the active partition.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] If all else fails, it should issue an INT 18h BIOS interrupt call (followed by an INT 19h just in case INT 18h would return) in order to give back control to the BIOS, which would then attempt to boot off other devices, attempt a remote boot via network.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Many modern systems (Intel Macs and newer PCs) use UEFI.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Unlike BIOS, UEFI (not **Legacy boot** via CSM) does not rely on boot sectors, UEFI system loads the boot loader (**EFI application** file in USB disk or in the EFI System Partition) directly, and the OS kernel is loaded by the boot loader.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] It is difficult to hardwire all the required logic for handling such devices, so an integrated boot ROM is used instead in such scenarios.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Also, a boot ROM may be able to load a boot loader or diagnostic program via serial interfaces like UART, SPI, USB and so on.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This feature is often used for system recovery purposes, or it could also be used for initial non-volatile memory programming when there is no software available in the non-volatile memory yet.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Many modern microcontrollers (e.g., flash memory controller on USB flash drives) have firmware ROM integrated directly into their silicon.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some embedded system designs may also include an intermediary boot sequence step.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] For example, Das U-Boot may be split into two stages: the platform would load a small SPL (Secondary Program Loader), which is a stripped-down version of U-Boot, and the SPL would do some initial hardware configuration (e.g.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] DRAM initialization using CPU cache as RAM) and load the larger, fully featured version of U-Boot.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Such embedded systems may used highly customized and vertical integrated hardware and software, and their boot programs may be simpler.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some CPUs and SoCs may not use CPU cache as RAM on boot process, they use an integrated boot processor to do some hardware configuration to reduce cost.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] It is also possible to take control of a system by using a hardware debug interface such as JTAG.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Such an interface may be used to write the boot loader program into bootable non-volatile memory (e.g. flash) by instructing the processor core to perform the necessary actions to program non-volatile memory.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Alternatively, the debug interface may be used to upload some diagnostic or boot code into RAM, and then to start the processor core and instruct it to execute the uploaded code.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] This allows, for example, the recovery of embedded systems where no software remains on any supported boot device, and where the processor does not have any integrated boot ROM.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] JTAG is a standard and popular interface; many CPUs, microcontrollers and other devices are manufactured with JTAG interfaces (as of 2009).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some microcontrollers provide special hardware interfaces that cannot be used to take arbitrary control of a system or directly run code, but instead allow the insertion of boot code into bootable non-volatile memory (like flash memory) via simple protocols.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Then, at the manufacturing phase, such interfaces are used to inject boot code (and possibly other code) into non-volatile memory.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] After system reset, the microcontroller begins to execute code programmed into its non-volatile memory, just like usual processors use ROMs for booting.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Most notably, this technique is used by Atmel AVR microcontrollers, and by others as well.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In many cases, such interfaces are implemented by hardwired logic.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In other cases, such interfaces could be created by software running in integrated on-chip boot ROM from GPIO pins.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Most DSPs have a serial mode boot and a parallel mode boot, such as the host port interface (HPI boot).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In the case of DSPs, there is often a second microprocessor or microcontroller present in the system design, and this is responsible for overall system behavior, interrupt handling, dealing with external events, user interface, etc., while the DSP is dedicated to signal processing tasks only.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In such systems, the DSP could be booted by another processor, which is sometimes referred as the *host processor* (giving name to a Host Port).
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Such a processor is also sometimes referred to as the *master*, since it usually boots first from its own memories and then controls overall system behavior, including booting of the DSP, and then further controls the DSP's behavior.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The DSP often lacks its own boot memories and relies on the host processor to supply the required code instead.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The most notable systems with such a design are cell phones, modems, audio and video players and so on, where a DSP and a CPU/microcontroller coexist.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Many FPGA chips load their configuration from an external configuration ROM, typically a serial EEPROM, on power-up.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Various measures have been implemented that enhance the security of the booting process.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Some of them are made mandatory, others can be disabled or enabled by the end user.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Traditionally, booting did not involve the use of cryptography.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The security can be bypassed by unlocking the boot loader, which might or might not be approved by the manufacturer.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Modern boot loaders make use of concurrency, meaning they can run multiple processor cores and threads at the same time, which adds extra layers of complexity to secure booting.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Matthew Garrett argued that booting security serves a legitimate goal, but in doing so chooses defaults that are hostile to users.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] The system might exhibit its erroneous state in, for example, an explicit bootloop or a blue screen of death, before recovery is indicated.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Detection of an erroneous state may require a distributed event store and stream-processing platform for real-time operation of a distributed system.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] An erroneous state can trigger bootloops; this state can be caused by misconfiguration from previously known-good operations.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Recovery attempts from that erroneous state then enter a reboot, in an attempt to return to a known-good state.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] In Windows OS operations, for example, the recovery procedure was to reboot three times, the reboots needed to return to a usable menu.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] Recovery might be specified via Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML), which can also implement Single sign-on (SSO) for some applications; in the zero trust security model, identification, authorization, and authentication are separable concerns in an SSO session.
[src:embedded-systems/booting] When recovery of a site is indicated (viz., a blue screen of death is displayed on an airport terminal screen) personal site visits might be required to remediate the situation.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] A **cross compiler** is a compiler capable of creating executable code for a platform other than the one on which the compiler is running.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] For example, a compiler that runs on a PC but generates code that runs on Android devices is a cross compiler.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] A cross compiler is useful to compile code for multiple platforms from one development host.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Direct compilation on the target platform might be infeasible, for example on embedded systems with limited computing resources.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Cross compilers are distinct from source-to-source compilers.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] A cross compiler is for cross-platform software generation of machine code, while a source-to-source compiler translates from one coding language to another in text code.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The fundamental use of a cross compiler is to separate the build environment from target environment.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Use of virtual machines (such as Java's JVM) resolves some of the reasons for which cross compilers were developed.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The virtual machine paradigm allows the same compiler output to be used across multiple target systems, although this is not always ideal because virtual machines are often slower and the compiled program can only be run on computers with that virtual machine.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The **Canadian Cross** is a technique for building cross compilers for other machines, where the original machine is much slower or less convenient than the target.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Given three machines A, B, and C, one uses machine A (e.g. running Windows XP on an IA-32 processor) to build a cross compiler that runs on machine B (e.g. running macOS on an x86-64 processor) to create executables for machine C (e.g. running Android on an ARM processor).
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The practical advantage in this example is that Machine A is slow but has a proprietary compiler, while Machine B is fast but has no compiler at all, and Machine C is impractically slow to be used for compilation.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The end-result cross compiler (4) will not be able to run on build machine A; instead it would run on machine B to compile an application into executable code that would then be copied to machine C and executed on machine C.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] For instance, NetBSD provides a POSIX Unix shell script named `build.sh` which will first build its own toolchain with the host's compiler; this, in turn, will be used to build the cross compiler which will be used to build the whole system.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The term **Canadian Cross** came about because at the time that these issues were under discussion, Canada had three national political parties.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] GCC, a free software collection of compilers, can be set up to cross compile.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] It supports many platforms and languages.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] GCC requires that a compiled copy of binutils is available for each targeted platform.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Especially important is the GNU Assembler.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Therefore, binutils first has to be compiled correctly with the switch `--target=some-target` sent to the configure script.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] GCC also has to be configured with the same `--target` option.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Cross-compiling GCC requires that a portion of the *target platform'*s C standard library be available on the *host platform*.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The programmer may choose to compile the full C library, but this choice could be unreliable.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The alternative is to use newlib, which is a small C library containing only the most essential components required to compile C source code.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The GNU Autotools packages (i.e. autoconf, automake, and libtool) use the notion of a *build platform*, a *host platform*, and a *target platform*.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The *build platform* is where the compiler is actually compiled.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] In most cases, build should be left undefined (it will default from host).
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The *host platform* is always where the output artifacts from the compiler will be executed whether the output is another compiler or not.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The *target platform* is used when cross-compiling cross compilers, it represents what type of object code the package will produce; otherwise the *target platform* setting is irrelevant.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] For example, consider cross-compiling a video game that will run on a Dreamcast.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The machine where the game is compiled is the *build platform* while the Dreamcast is the *host platform*.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The names *host* and *target* are relative to the compiler being used and shifted like *son* and *grandson*.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Another method popularly used by embedded Linux developers involves the combination of GCC compilers with specialized sandboxes like Scratchbox and Scratchbox 2, or PRoot.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] These tools create a "chrooted" sandbox where the programmer can build up necessary tools, libc, and libraries without having to set extra paths.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Facilities are also provided to "deceive" the runtime so that it "believes" it is actually running on the intended target CPU (such as an ARM architecture); this allows configuration scripts and the like to run without error.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Scratchbox runs more slowly by comparison to "non-chrooted" methods, and most tools that are on the host must be moved into Scratchbox to function.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Manx Software Systems, of Shrewsbury, New Jersey, produced C compilers beginning in the 1980s targeted at professional developers for a variety of platforms up to and including IBM PC compatibles and Macs.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Manx's Aztec C programming language was available for a variety of platforms including MS-DOS, Apple II, DOS 3.3 and ProDOS, Commodore 64, Mac 68k and Amiga.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] From the 1980s and continuing throughout the 1990s until Manx Software Systems disappeared, the MS-DOS version of Aztec C was offered both as a native mode compiler or as a cross compiler for other platforms with different processors including the Commodore 64 and Apple II.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Internet distributions still exist for Aztec C including their MS-DOS based cross compilers.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Manx's Aztec C86, their native mode 8086 MS-DOS compiler, was also a cross compiler.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Although it did not compile code for a different processor like their Aztec C65 6502 cross compilers for the Commodore 64 and Apple II, it created binary executables for then-legacy operating systems for the 16-bit 8086 family of processors.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] When the IBM PC was first introduced it was available with a choice of operating systems, CP/M-86 and PC DOS being two of them.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Aztec C86 was provided with link libraries for generating code for both IBM PC operating systems.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Throughout the 1980s later versions of Aztec C86 (3.xx, 4.xx and 5.xx) added support for MS-DOS "transitory" versions 1 and 2 and which were less robust than the "baseline" MS-DOS version 3 and later which Aztec C86 targeted until its demise.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Finally, Aztec C86 provided C language developers with the ability to produce ROM-able "HEX" code which could then be transferred using a ROM burner directly to an 8086 based processor.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Paravirtualization may be more common today but the practice of creating low-level ROM code was more common per-capita during those years when device driver development was often done by application programmers for individual applications, and new devices amounted to a cottage industry.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] It was not uncommon for application programmers to interface directly with hardware without support from the manufacturer.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] This practice was similar to Embedded Systems Development today.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Thomas Fenwick and James Goodnow II were the two principal developers of Aztec-C.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Fenwick later became notable as the author of the Microsoft Windows CE kernel or NK ("New Kernel") as it was then called.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Microsoft C (MSC) has a shorter history than others dating back to the 1980s.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The first Microsoft C Compilers were made by the same company who made Lattice C and were rebranded by Microsoft as their own, until MSC 4 was released, which was the first version that Microsoft produced themselves.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] In 1987, many developers started switching to Microsoft C, and many more would follow throughout the development of Microsoft Windows to its present state.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Products like Clipper and later Clarion emerged that offered easy database application development by using cross language techniques, allowing part of their programs to be compiled with Microsoft C.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Borland C (California company) was available for purchase years before Microsoft released its first C product.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] C programs had long been linked with modules written in assembly language.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Most C compilers (even current compilers) offer an assembly language pass (that can be tweaked for efficiency then linked to the rest of the program after assembling).
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] By 1987, with the release of MSC 5.1, Microsoft offered a cross language development environment for MS-DOS.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] 16-bit binary object code written in assembly language (MASM) and Microsoft's other languages including QuickBASIC, Pascal, and Fortran could be linked together into one program, in a process they called "Mixed Language Programming" and now "InterLanguage Calling".
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] If BASIC was used in this mix, the main program needed to be in BASIC to support the internal runtime system that compiled BASIC required for garbage collection and its other managed operations that simulated a BASIC interpreter like QBasic in MS-DOS.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The calling convention for C code, in particular, was to pass parameters in "reverse order" on the stack and return values on the stack rather than in a processor register.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] There were other programming rules to make all the languages work together, but this particular rule persisted through the cross language development that continued throughout Windows 16- and 32-bit versions and in the development of programs for OS/2, and which persists to this day.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] It is known as the Pascal calling convention.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Another type of cross compilation that Microsoft C was used for during this time was in retail applications that require handheld devices like the Symbol Technologies PDT3100 (used to take inventory), which provided a link library targeted at an 8088 based barcode reader.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The application was built on the host computer then transferred to the handheld device (via a serial cable) where it was run, similar to what is done today for that same market using Windows Mobile by companies like Motorola, who bought Symbol.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Throughout the 1990s and beginning with MSC 6 (their first ANSI C compliant compiler) Microsoft re-focused their C compilers on the emerging Windows market, and also on OS/2 and in the development of GUI programs.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Mixed language compatibility remained through MSC 6 on the MS-DOS side, but the API for Microsoft Windows 3.0 and 3.1 was written in MSC 6.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] MSC 6 was also extended to provide support for 32-bit assemblies and support for the emerging Windows for Workgroups and Windows NT which would form the foundation for Windows XP.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] A programming practice called a thunk was introduced to allow passing between 16- and 32-bit programs that took advantage of runtime binding (dynamic linking) rather than the static binding that was favoured in monolithic 16-bit MS-DOS applications.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Static binding is still favoured by some native code developers but does not generally provide the degree of code reuse required by newer best practices like the Capability Maturity Model (CMM).
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] MS-DOS support was still provided with the release of Microsoft's first C++ Compiler, MSC 7, which was backwardly compatible with the C programming language and MS-DOS and supported both 16- and 32-bit code generation.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] MS-DOS and 16-bit code generation support continued until MSC 8.00c which was bundled with Microsoft C++ and Microsoft Application Studio 1.5, the forerunner of Microsoft Visual Studio which is the cross development environment that Microsoft provide today.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] MSC 12 was released with Microsoft Visual Studio 6 and no longer provided support for MS-DOS 16-bit binaries, instead providing support for 32-bit console applications, but provided support for Windows 95 and Windows 98 code generation as well as for Windows NT.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Link libraries were available for other processors that ran Microsoft Windows; a practice that Microsoft continues to this day.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] MSC 13 was released with Visual Studio 2003, and MSC 14 was released with Visual Studio 2005, both of which still produce code for older systems like Windows 95, but which will produce code for several target platforms including the mobile market and the ARM architecture.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] In 2001 Microsoft developed the Common Language Runtime (CLR), which formed the core for their .NET Framework compiler in the Visual Studio IDE.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] This layer on the operating system which is in the API allows the mixing of development languages compiled across platforms that run the Windows operating system.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The .NET Framework runtime and CLR provide a mapping layer to the core routines for the processor and the devices on the target computer.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The command-line C compiler in Visual Studio will compile native code for a variety of processors and can be used to build the core routines themselves.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Runtime libraries, such as Mono, provide compatibility for cross-compiled .NET programs to other operating systems, such as Linux.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Libraries like Qt and its predecessors including XVT provide source code level cross development capability with other platforms, while still using Microsoft C to build the Windows versions.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Other compilers like MinGW have also become popular in this area since they are more directly compatible with the Unixes that comprise the non-Windows side of software development allowing those developers to target all platforms using a familiar build environment.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Free Pascal was developed from the beginning as a cross compiler.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The compiler executable (ppcXXX where XXX is a target architecture) is capable of producing executables (or just object files if no internal linker exists, or even just assembly files if no internal assembler exists) for all OS of the same architecture.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] For example, ppc386 is capable of producing executables for i386-linux, i386-win32, i386-go32v2 (DOS) and all other OSes (see ).
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] For compiling to another architecture, however, a cross architecture version of the compiler must be built first.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The resulting compiler executable would have additional 'ross' before the target architecture in its name. i.e. if the compiler is built to target x64, then the executable would be ppcrossx64.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] To compile for a chosen architecture-OS, the compiler switch (for the compiler driver fpc) -P and -T can be used.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] This is also done when cross-compiling the compiler itself, but is set via make option CPU_TARGET and OS_TARGET.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] GNU assembler and linker for the target platform is required if Free Pascal does not yet have internal version of the tools for the target platform.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] Clang is natively a cross compiler, at build time you can select which architectures you want Clang to be able to target by using the `-target` flag.
[src:embedded-systems/cross-compiler] The heterogenous system Plan 9 and its toolchain does not distinguish between cross and native compilation.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Without DMA, programmed input–output must be used to transfer data which typically fully occupies the CPU for the entire duration of the transfer, and is thus unavailable to perform other work.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] With DMA, the CPU first initiates the transfer, then it does other operations while the transfer is in progress, and it finally receives an interrupt from the **direct memory access controller** (**DMAC**) when the operation is done.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] This feature is useful at any time that the CPU cannot keep up with the rate of data transfer, or when the CPU needs to perform work while waiting for a relatively slow data transfer.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Many hardware systems use DMA, including disk drive controllers, graphics cards, network cards, sound cards and dedicated DMA controllers (acting on behalf of the aforementioned device types).
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] DMA is also used for intra-chip data transfer in some multi-core processors.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Computers that have DMA capability can transfer data to and from devices with much less CPU overhead than computers without DMA.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] DMA can also be used for *memory-to-memory* transfers.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] DMA can offload expensive memory operations, such as large copies or scatter-gather operations, from the CPU to a DMA controller.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] An implementation example is the I/O Acceleration Technology.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] DMA is of interest in network-on-chip and in-memory computing architectures.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] While hardware acceleration is usually vendor-specific, direct memory access can be used by the class driver.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Standard DMA, also called third-party DMA, uses a DMA controller.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] A DMA controller can generate memory addresses and initiate memory read or write cycles.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] It contains several hardware registers that can be written and read by the CPU.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] These include a memory address register, a count register, and one or more control registers.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Depending on what features the DMA controller provides, these control registers might specify some combination of the source, the destination, the direction of the transfer (reading from the I/O device or writing to the I/O device).
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] To carry out an input, output or memory-to-memory operation, the host processor initializes the DMA controller with a count of the number of words to transfer, and the memory address to use.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The CPU then commands the peripheral device to initiate a data transfer.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The DMA controller then provides addresses and read/write control lines to the system memory.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Each time a byte of data is ready to be transferred between the peripheral device and memory, the DMA controller increments its internal address register until the full block of data is transferred.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] In a bus mastering system, also known as a **first-party** DMA system, the CPU and peripherals can each be granted control of the memory bus.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Where a peripheral can become a bus master, it can directly write to system memory without the involvement of the CPU, providing memory address and control signals as required.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Some measures must be provided to put the processor into a hold condition so that bus contention does not occur.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The peripheral itself may have hardware registers, such as address and count registers, to control the DMA operation.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] In *burst mode*, an entire block of data is transferred in one contiguous sequence.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Once the DMA controller is granted access to the system bus by the CPU, it transfers all bytes of data in the data block before releasing control of the system bus back to the CPU, but renders the CPU inactive for relatively long periods of time.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The mode is also called "Block Transfer Mode".
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The *cycle stealing mode* is used in systems in which the CPU should not be disabled for the length of time needed for burst transfer modes.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] In the cycle stealing mode, the DMA controller obtains access to the system bus the same way as in burst mode, using *BR (Bus Request)* and *BG (Bus Grant)* signals, which are the two signals controlling the interface between the CPU and the DMA controller.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] However, in cycle-stealing mode, after one unit of data transfer, the control of the system bus is deasserted to the CPU via BG.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] It is then continually requested again via BR, transferring one unit of data per request, until the entire block of data has been transferred.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] By continually obtaining and releasing the control of the system bus, the DMA controller essentially interleaves instruction and data transfers.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The CPU processes an instruction, then the DMA controller transfers one data value, and so on.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Data is not transferred as quickly, but the CPU is not idled for as long as in burst mode.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Cycle-stealing mode is useful for controllers that monitor data in real time.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Transparent mode takes the most time to transfer a block of data, yet it is also the most efficient mode in terms of overall system performance.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] In transparent mode, the DMA controller transfers data only when the CPU is performing operations that do not use the system buses.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The primary advantage of transparent mode is that the CPU never stops executing its programs, and the DMA transfer is free in terms of time, while the disadvantage is that the hardware needs to determine when the CPU is not using the system buses, which can be complex.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] This is also called "*Hidden DMA data transfer mode*".
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] DMA can lead to cache coherency problems.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Imagine a CPU equipped with a cache and an external memory that can be accessed directly by devices using DMA.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] When the CPU accesses location X in the memory, the current value will be stored in the cache.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Subsequent operations on X will update the cached copy of X, but not the external memory version of X, assuming a write-back cache.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] If the cache is not flushed to the memory before the next time a device tries to access X, the device will receive a stale value of X.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Similarly, if the cached copy of X is not invalidated when a device writes a new value to the memory, then the CPU will operate on a stale value of X.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] This issue can be addressed in one of two ways in system design: Cache-coherent systems implement a method in hardware, called bus snooping, whereby external writes are signaled to the cache controller which then performs a cache invalidation for DMA writes or cache flush for DMA reads.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Non-coherent systems leave this to software, where the OS must then ensure that the cache lines are flushed before an outgoing DMA transfer is started and invalidated before a memory range affected by an incoming DMA transfer is accessed.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The OS must make sure that the memory range is not accessed by any running threads in the meantime.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The latter approach introduces some overhead to the DMA operation, as most hardware requires a loop to invalidate each cache line individually.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Hybrids also exist, where the secondary L2 cache is coherent while the L1 cache (typically on-CPU) is managed by software.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] In the original IBM PC (and the follow-up PC/XT), there was only one Intel 8237 DMA controller capable of providing four DMA channels (numbered 0–3).
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Additionally, the controller could only be used for transfers to, from or between expansion bus I/O devices, as the 8237 could only perform memory-to-memory transfers using channels 0 & 1, of which channel 0 in the PC (& XT) was dedicated to dynamic memory refresh.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] This prevented it from being used as a general-purpose "Blitter", and consequently, block memory moves in the PC, limited by the general PIO speed of the CPU, were very slow.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] ISA DMA's extended 24-bit address bus width allows it to access up to 16 MB of lower memory.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The page register was also rewired to address the full 16 MB memory address space of the 80286 CPU.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] They were supported to the extent that they are required to support built-in legacy PC hardware on later machines.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] In cases where an original 8237s or direct compatibles were still used, transfer to or from these devices may still be limited to the first 16 MB of main RAM regardless of the system's actual address space or amount of installed memory.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Each DMA channel has a 16-bit address register and a 16-bit count register associated with it.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] To initiate a data transfer, the device driver sets up the DMA channel's address and count registers together with the direction of the data transfer, read or write.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] It then instructs the DMA hardware to begin the transfer.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] When the transfer is complete, the device interrupts the CPU.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Scatter-gather or vectored I/O DMA allows the transfer of data to and from multiple memory areas in a single DMA transaction.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] It is equivalent to the chaining together of multiple simple DMA requests.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The motivation is to offload multiple input/output interrupt and data copy tasks from the CPU.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] DRQ stands for *Data request*; DACK for *Data acknowledge*.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] These symbols, seen on hardware schematics of computer systems with DMA functionality, represent electronic signaling lines between the CPU and DMA controller.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Each DMA channel has one Request and one Acknowledge line.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] A device that uses DMA must be configured to use both lines of the assigned DMA channel.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] A PCI architecture has no central DMA controller, unlike ISA.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Instead, A PCI device can request control of the bus ("become the bus master") and request to read from and write to system memory.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] More precisely, a PCI component requests bus ownership from the PCI bus controller (usually PCI host bridge, and PCI to PCI bridge), which will arbitrate if several devices request bus ownership simultaneously, since there can only be one bus master at one time.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] When the component is granted ownership, it will issue normal read and write commands on the PCI bus, which will be claimed by the PCI bus controller.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] As an example, on an Intel Core-based PC, the southbridge will forward the transactions to the memory controller (which is integrated on the CPU die) using DMI, which will in turn convert them to DDR operations and send them out on the memory bus.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] As a result, there are quite a number of steps involved in a PCI DMA transfer; however, that poses little problem, since the PCI device or PCI bus itself are an order of magnitude slower than the rest of the components (see list of device bandwidths).
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] A modern x86 CPU may use more than 4 GB of memory, either utilizing the native 64-bit mode of x86-64 CPU, or the Physical Address Extension (PAE), a 36-bit addressing mode.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] In such a case, a device using DMA with a 32-bit address bus is unable to address memory above the 4 GB line.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] The new Double Address Cycle (DAC) mechanism, if implemented on both the PCI bus and the device itself, enables 64-bit DMA addressing.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Otherwise, the operating system would need to work around the problem by either using costly double buffers (DOS/Windows nomenclature) also known as bounce buffers (FreeBSD/Linux), or it could use an IOMMU to provide address translation services if one is present.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] As an example of DMA engine incorporated in a general-purpose CPU, some Intel Xeon chipsets include a DMA engine called I/O Acceleration Technology (I/OAT), which can offload memory copying from the main CPU, freeing it to do other work.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] In 2006, Intel's Linux kernel developer Andrew Grover performed benchmarks using I/OAT to offload network traffic copies and found no more than 10% improvement in CPU utilization with receiving workloads.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Further performance-oriented enhancements to the DMA mechanism have been introduced in Intel Xeon E5 processors with their **Data Direct I/O** (**DDIO**) feature, allowing the DMA "windows" to reside within CPU caches instead of system RAM.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] As a result, CPU caches are used as the primary source and destination for I/O, allowing network interface controllers (NICs) to DMA directly to the last-level cache (L3 cache) of local CPUs and avoid costly fetching of the I/O data from system RAM.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] In systems-on-a-chip and embedded systems, typical system bus infrastructure is a complex on-chip bus such as AMBA High-performance Bus.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] AMBA defines two kinds of AHB components: master and slave.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] A slave interface is similar to programmed I/O through which the software (running on an embedded CPU, e.g., ARM) can write/read I/O registers or (less commonly) local memory blocks inside the device.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] A master interface can be used by the device to perform DMA transactions to/from system memory without heavily loading the CPU.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Therefore, high bandwidth devices such as network controllers that need to transfer huge amounts of data to/from system memory will have two interface adapters to the AHB: a master and a slave interface.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] This is because on-chip buses like AHB do not support tri-stating the bus or alternating the direction of any line on the bus.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Like PCI, no central DMA controller is required since the DMA is bus-mastering, but an arbiter is required in case of multiple masters present on the system.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Internally, a multichannel DMA engine is usually present in the device to perform multiple concurrent scatter-gather operations as programmed by the software.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] As an example usage of DMA in a multiprocessor-system-on-chip, IBM/Sony/Toshiba's Cell processor incorporates a DMA engine for each of its 9 processing elements, including one Power processor element (PPE) and eight synergistic processor elements (SPEs).
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Since the SPE's load/store instructions can read/write only its own local memory, an SPE entirely depends on DMAs to transfer data to and from the main memory and local memories of other SPEs.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Thus, the DMA acts as a primary means of data transfer among cores inside this CPU (in contrast to cache-coherent CMP architectures such as Intel's cancelled general-purpose GPU, Larrabee).
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] DMA in Cell is fully cache coherent (note, however, local stores of SPEs operated upon by DMA do not act as globally coherent cache in the standard sense).
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] In both read ("get") and write ("put"), a DMA command can transfer either a single block area of size up to 16 KB, or a list of 2 to 2048 such blocks.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] According to an experiment, an effective peak performance of DMA in Cell (3 GHz, under uniform traffic) reaches 200 GB per second.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] Processors with scratchpad memory and DMA (such as digital signal processors and the Cell processor) may benefit from software overlapping DMA memory operations with processing, via double buffering or multibuffering.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] For example, the on-chip memory is split into two buffers; the processor may be operating on data in one, while the DMA engine is loading and storing data in the other.
[src:embedded-systems/direct-memory-access] This allows the system to avoid memory latency and exploit burst transfers, at the expense of needing a predictable memory access pattern.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] An **embedded system** is a specialized computer system—a combination of a computer processor, computer memory, and input/output peripheral devices—that has a dedicated function within a larger mechanical or electronic system.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] It is embedded as part of a complete device, often including electrical or electronic hardware and mechanical parts.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded systems control many devices in common use.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In 2009, it was estimated that 98% of all microprocessors manufactured were used in embedded systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Because an embedded system typically controls physical operations of the machine that it is embedded within, it often has real-time computing constraints.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Modern embedded systems are often based on microcontrollers (i.e., microprocessors with integrated memory and peripheral interfaces), but ordinary microprocessors (using external chips for memory and peripheral interface circuits) are also common, especially in more complex systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In either case, the processor(s) used may be types ranging from general purpose to those specialized in a certain class of computations, or even custom designed for the application at hand.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] A common standard class of dedicated processors is the digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Since the embedded system is dedicated to specific tasks, design engineers can optimize it to reduce the size and cost of the product and increase its reliability and performance.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are mass-produced, benefiting from economies of scale.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded systems range in size from portable personal devices such as digital watches and MP3 players to bigger machines like home appliances, industrial assembly lines, robots, transport vehicles, traffic light controllers, and medical imaging systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Often they constitute subsystems of other machines like avionics in aircraft and astrionics in spacecraft.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Large installations like factories, pipelines, and electrical grids rely on multiple embedded systems networked together.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Generalized through software customization, embedded systems such as programmable logic controllers frequently comprise their functional units.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The origins of the microprocessor and the microcontroller can be traced back to the MOS integrated circuit, which is an integrated circuit chip fabricated from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors) and was developed in the early 1960s.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor system could be contained on several MOS LSI chips.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released in 1971.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] One of the first recognizably modern embedded systems was the Apollo Guidance Computer, developed ca.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] 1965 by Charles Stark Draper at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] At the project's inception, the Apollo guidance computer was considered the riskiest item in the Apollo project as it employed the then newly developed monolithic integrated circuits to reduce the computer's size and weight.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] An early mass-produced embedded system was the Autonetics D-17 guidance computer for the Minuteman missile, released in 1961.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] When the Minuteman II went into production in 1966, the D-17 was replaced with a new computer that represented the first high-volume use of integrated circuits.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Since these early applications in the 1960s, embedded systems have come down in price and there has been a dramatic rise in processing power and functionality.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] An early microprocessor, the Intel 4004 (released in 1971), was designed for calculators and other small systems but still required external memory and support chips.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] By the early 1980s, memory, input and output system components had been integrated into the same chip as the processor, forming a microcontroller.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Microcontrollers find applications where a general-purpose computer would be too costly.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] As the cost of microprocessors and microcontrollers fell, the prevalence of embedded systems increased.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] A comparatively low-cost microcontroller may be programmed to fulfill the same role as a large number of separate components.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] With microcontrollers, it became feasible to replace, even in consumer products, expensive knob-based analog components such as potentiometers and variable capacitors with up/down buttons or knobs read out by a microprocessor.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Although in this context an embedded system is usually more complex than a traditional solution, most of the complexity is contained within the microcontroller itself.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Very few additional components may be needed and most of the design effort is in the software.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Software prototype and test can be quicker compared with the design and construction of a new circuit not using an embedded processor.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded systems are commonly found in consumer, industrial, automotive, home appliances, medical, telecommunication, commercial, aerospace and military applications.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Telecommunications systems employ numerous embedded systems from telephone switches for the network to cell phones at the end user.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Computer networking uses dedicated routers and network bridges to route data.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Consumer electronics include MP3 players, television sets, mobile phones, video game consoles, digital cameras, GPS receivers, and printers.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Household appliances, such as microwave ovens, washing machines and dishwashers, include embedded systems to provide flexibility, efficiency and features.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems use networked thermostats to more accurately and efficiently control temperature that can change by time of day and season.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Home automation uses wired and wireless networking that can be used to control lights, climate, security, audio/visual, surveillance, etc., all of which use embedded devices for sensing and controlling.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Transportation systems from flight to automobiles increasingly use embedded systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] New airplanes contain advanced avionics such as inertial guidance systems and GPS receivers that also have considerable safety requirements.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Spacecraft rely on astrionics systems for trajectory correction.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Various electric motors — brushless DC motors, induction motors and DC motors — use electronic motor controllers.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Automobiles, electric vehicles, and hybrid vehicles increasingly use embedded systems to maximize efficiency and reduce pollution.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Other automotive safety systems using embedded systems include anti-lock braking system (ABS), electronic stability control (ESC/ESP), traction control (TCS) and automatic four-wheel drive.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Medical equipment uses embedded systems for monitoring, and various medical imaging (positron emission tomography (PET), single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for non-invasive internal inspections.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded systems within medical equipment are often powered by industrial computers.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded systems are used for safety-critical systems in aerospace and defense industries.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Unless connected to wired or wireless networks via on-chip 3G cellular or other methods for IoT monitoring and control purposes, these systems can be isolated from hacking and thus be more secure.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] For fire safety, the systems can be designed to have a greater ability to handle higher temperatures and continue to operate.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In dealing with security, the embedded systems can be self-sufficient and be able to deal with cut electrical and communication systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Miniature wireless devices called motes are networked wireless sensors.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] These motes are completely self-contained and will typically run off a battery source for years before the batteries need to be changed or charged.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded systems are designed to perform a specific task, in contrast with general-purpose computers designed for multiple tasks.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Some have real-time performance constraints that must be met, for reasons such as safety and usability; others may have low or no performance requirements, allowing the system hardware to be simplified to reduce costs.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded systems are not always standalone devices.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Many embedded systems are a small part within a larger device that serves a more general purpose.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] For example, the Gibson Robot Guitar features an embedded system for tuning the strings, but the overall purpose of the Robot Guitar is to play music.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Similarly, an embedded system in an automobile provides a specific function as a subsystem of the car itself.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The program instructions written for embedded systems are referred to as firmware, and are stored in read-only memory or flash memory chips.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] They run with limited computer hardware resources: little memory, small or non-existent keyboard or screen.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded systems range from no user interface at all, in systems dedicated to one task, to complex graphical user interfaces that resemble modern computer desktop operating systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Simple embedded devices use buttons, light-emitting diodes (LED), graphic or character liquid-crystal displays (LCD) with a simple menu system.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] More sophisticated devices that use a graphical screen with touch sensing or screen-edge soft keys provide flexibility while minimizing space used: the meaning of the buttons can change with the screen, and selection involves the natural behavior of pointing at what is desired.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Some systems provide user interface remotely with the help of a serial (e.g.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] This approach extends the capabilities of the embedded system, avoids the cost of a display, simplifies the board support package (BSP) and allows designers to build a rich user interface on the PC.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] A good example of this is the combination of an embedded HTTP server running on an embedded device (such as an IP camera or a network router).
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The user interface is displayed in a web browser on a PC connected to the device.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Examples of properties of typical embedded computers when compared with general-purpose counterparts are low power consumption, small size, rugged operating ranges, and low per-unit cost.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] This comes at the expense of limited processing resources.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Numerous microcontrollers have been developed for embedded systems use.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] General-purpose microprocessors are also used in embedded systems, but generally require more support circuitry than microcontrollers.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] PC/104 and PC/104+ are examples of standards for ready-made computer boards intended for small, low-volume embedded and ruggedized systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] These are mostly x86-based and often physically small compared to a standard PC, although still large compared to most simple (8/16-bit) embedded systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] They may use a standard operating system such as Linux or NetBSD or an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS) such as MicroC/OS-II, QNX or VxWorks.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In certain applications, where small size or power efficiency are not primary concerns, the components used may be compatible with those used in general-purpose x86 personal computers.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Boards such as the VIA EPIA range help to bridge the gap by being PC-compatible but highly integrated, physically smaller or have other attributes making them attractive to embedded engineers.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The advantage of this approach is that low-cost commodity components may be used along with the same software development tools used for general software development.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Systems built in this way are still regarded as embedded since they are integrated into larger devices and fulfill a single role.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Examples of devices that may adopt this approach are automated teller machines (ATM) and arcade machines, which contain code specific to the application.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] However, most ready-made embedded systems boards are not PC-centered and do not use the ISA or PCI buses.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] When a system-on-a-chip processor is involved, there may be little benefit to having a standardized bus connecting discrete components, and the environment for both hardware and software tools may be very different.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] One common design style uses a small system module, perhaps the size of a business card, holding high density BGA chips such as an ARM-based system-on-a-chip processor and peripherals, external flash memory for storage, and DRAM for runtime memory.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The module vendor will usually provide boot software and make sure there is a selection of operating systems, usually including Linux and some real-time choices.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] These modules can be manufactured in high volume, by organizations familiar with their specialized testing issues and combined with much lower volume custom mainboards with application-specific external peripherals.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Prominent examples of this approach include Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] A system on a chip (SoC) contains a complete system - consisting of multiple processors, multipliers, caches, even different types of memory and commonly various peripherals like interfaces for wired or wireless communication on a single chip.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Often graphics processing units (GPU) and DSPs are included such chips.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] SoCs can be implemented as an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) or using a field-programmable gate array (FPGA), which typically can be reconfigured.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] ASIC implementations are common for very-high-volume embedded systems like mobile phones and smartphones.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] ASIC or FPGA implementations may be used for not-so-high-volume embedded systems with special needs in terms of signal processing performance, interfaces and reliability, like in avionics.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] As with other software, embedded system designers use compilers, assemblers, and debuggers to develop embedded system software.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded software often requires a variety of development tools, including programming languages such as C++, Rust, or Python, and frameworks like Qt for graphical interfaces.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] These tools enable developers to create efficient, scalable, and feature-rich applications tailored to the specific requirements of embedded systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The choice of tools is driven by factors such as real-time performance, integration with hardware, or energy efficiency.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] As the complexity of embedded systems grows, higher-level tools and operating systems are migrating into machinery where it makes sense.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] For example, cellphones, personal digital assistants and other consumer computers often need significant software that is purchased or provided by a person other than the manufacturer of the electronics.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In these systems, an open programming environment such as Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OSGi or Embedded Java is required so that the third-party software provider can sell to a large market.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded debugging may be performed at different levels, depending on the facilities available.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Unless restricted to external debugging, the programmer can typically load and run software through the tools, view the code running in the processor, and start or stop its operation.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The view of the code may be as high-level programming language, assembly code or a mixture of both.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Real-time operating systems often support tracing of operating system events.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] A graphical view is presented by a host PC tool, based on a recording of the system behavior.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The trace recording can be performed in software, by the RTOS, or by special tracing hardware.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] RTOS tracing allows developers to understand timing and performance issues of the software system and gives a good understanding of the high-level system behaviors.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Trace recording in embedded systems can be achieved using hardware or software solutions.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Software-based trace recording does not require specialized debugging hardware and can be used to record traces in deployed devices, but it can have an impact on CPU and RAM usage.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] One example of a software-based tracing method used in RTOS environments is the use of empty macros which are invoked by the operating system at strategic places in the code, and can be implemented to serve as hooks.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Embedded systems often reside in machines that are expected to run continuously for years without error, and in some cases, recover by themselves if an error occurs.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Therefore, the software is usually developed and tested more carefully than that for personal computers, and unreliable mechanical moving parts such as disk drives, switches or buttons are avoided.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] For high-volume systems such as mobile phones, minimizing cost is usually the primary design consideration.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Engineers typically select hardware that is just good enough to implement the necessary functions.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] For low-volume or prototype embedded systems, general-purpose computers may be adapted by limiting the programs or by replacing the operating system with an RTOS.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In 1978 National Electrical Manufacturers Association released ICS 3-1978, a standard for programmable microcontrollers, including almost any computer-based controllers, such as single-board computers, numerical, and event-based controllers.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] There are several different types of software architecture in common use.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In this design, the software simply has a loop which monitors the input devices.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The loop calls subroutines, each of which manages a part of the hardware or software.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Hence it is called a simple control loop or programmed input-output.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are predominantly controlled by interrupts.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] This means that tasks performed by the system are triggered by different kinds of events; an interrupt could be generated, for example, by a timer at a predefined interval, or by a serial port controller receiving data.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] This architecture is used if event handlers need low latency, and the event handlers are short and simple.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] These systems run a simple task in a main loop also, but this task is not very sensitive to unexpected delays.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Sometimes the interrupt handler will add longer tasks to a queue structure.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Later, after the interrupt handler has finished, these tasks are executed by the main loop.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] This method brings the system close to a multitasking kernel with discrete processes.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Cooperative multitasking is very similar to the simple control loop scheme, except that the loop is hidden in an API.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The programmer defines a series of tasks, and each task gets its own environment to run in.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] When a task is idle, it calls an idle routine, which passes control to another task.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of the control loop, except that adding new software is easier, by simply writing a new task, or adding to the queue.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In this type of system, a low-level piece of code switches between tasks or threads based on a timer that invokes an interrupt.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] This is the level at which the system is generally considered to have an operating system kernel.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Depending on how much functionality is required, it introduces more or less of the complexities associated with managing multiple tasks running conceptually in parallel.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Because of these complexities, it is common for organizations to use an off-the-shelf RTOS, allowing the application programmers to concentrate on device functionality rather than operating system services.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The choice to include an RTOS brings in its own issues, however, as the selection must be made prior to starting the application development process.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] This timing forces developers to choose the embedded operating system for their device based on current requirements and so restricts future options to a large extent.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] These trends are leading to the uptake of embedded middleware in addition to an RTOS.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] A microkernel allocates memory and switches the CPU to different threads of execution.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] User-mode processes implement major functions such as file systems, network interfaces, etc.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Exokernels communicate efficiently by normal subroutine calls.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] The hardware and all the software in the system are available to and extensible by application programmers.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] A monolithic kernel is a relatively large kernel with sophisticated capabilities adapted to suit an embedded environment.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] This gives programmers an environment similar to a desktop operating system like Linux or Microsoft Windows, and is therefore very productive for development.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] On the downside, it requires considerably more hardware resources, is often more expensive, and, because of the complexity of these kernels, can be less predictable and reliable.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Common examples of embedded monolithic kernels are embedded Linux, VXWorks and Windows CE.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] Despite the increased cost in hardware, this type of embedded system is increasing in popularity, especially on the more powerful embedded devices such as wireless routers and GPS navigation systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In addition to the core operating system, many embedded systems have additional upper-layer software components.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] These components include networking protocol stacks like CAN, TCP/IP, FTP, HTTP, and HTTPS, and storage capabilities like FAT and flash memory management systems.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] If the embedded device has audio and video capabilities, then the appropriate drivers and codecs will be present in the system.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In the case of the monolithic kernels, many of these software layers may be included in the kernel.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In the RTOS category, the availability of additional software components depends on the commercial offering.
[src:embedded-systems/embedded-system] In the automotive sector, AUTOSAR is a standard architecture for embedded software.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:embedded-systems/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Flash memory, a type of floating-gate memory, was invented by Fujio Masuoka at Toshiba in 1980 and is based on EEPROM technology.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Toshiba began marketing flash memory in 1987.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] EPROMs had to be erased completely before they could be rewritten.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND flash memory, however, may be erased, written, and read in blocks (or pages), which generally are much smaller than the entire device.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NOR flash memory allows a single machine word to be written – to an erased location – or read independently.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A flash memory device typically consists of one or more flash memory chips (each holding many flash memory cells), along with a separate flash memory controller chip.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The NAND type is found mainly in memory cards, USB flash drives, solid-state drives (those produced since 2009), feature phones, smartphones, and similar products, for general storage and transfer of data.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND or NOR flash memory is also often used to store configuration data in digital products, a task previously made possible by EEPROM or battery-powered static RAM.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A key disadvantage of flash memory is that it can endure only a relatively small number of write cycles in a specific block.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NOR flash is known for its direct random-access capabilities, making it apt for executing code directly.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Its architecture allows for individual byte access, facilitating faster read speeds compared to NAND flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND flash memory operates with a different architecture, relying on a serial access approach.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This makes NAND suitable for high-density data storage, but less efficient for random-access tasks.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND flash is often employed in scenarios where cost-effective, high-capacity storage is crucial, such as in USB drives, memory cards, and solid-state drives (SSDs).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The primary differentiator lies in their use cases and internal structures.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NOR flash is optimal for applications requiring quick access to individual bytes, as in embedded systems for program execution.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND flash, on the other hand, shines in scenarios demanding cost-effective, high-capacity storage with sequential data access.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Flash memory is used in computers, PDAs, digital audio players, digital cameras, mobile phones, synthesizers, video games, scientific instrumentation, industrial robotics, and medical electronics.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Flash memory has a fast read access time but is not as fast as static RAM or ROM.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In portable devices, it is preferred to use flash memory because of its mechanical shock resistance, since mechanical drives are more prone to mechanical damage.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Because erase cycles are slow, the large block sizes used in flash memory erasing give it a significant speed advantage over non-flash EEPROM when writing large amounts of data.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] As of 2019, flash memory costs much less than byte-programmable EEPROM and has become the dominant memory type wherever a system required a significant amount of non-volatile solid-state storage.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] EEPROMs, however, are still used in applications that require only small amounts of storage, e.g. in SPD implementations on computer-memory modules.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Flash memory packages can use die stacking with through-silicon vias and several dozen layers of 3D TLC NAND cells (per die) simultaneously to achieve capacities of up to 1 tebibyte per package using 16 stacked dies and an integrated flash controller as a separate die inside the package.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The origins of flash memory can be traced to the development of the floating-gate MOSFET (FGMOS), also known as the floating-gate transistor.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The original MOSFET was invented at Bell Labs between 1959 and 1960.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Dawon Kahng went on to develop a variation, the floating-gate MOSFET, with Taiwanese-American engineer Simon Min Sze at Bell Labs in 1967.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] They proposed that it could be used as floating-gate memory cells for storing a form of programmable read-only memory (PROM) that is both non-volatile and re-programmable.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Early types of floating-gate memory included EPROM (erasable PROM) and EEPROM (electrically erasable PROM) in the 1970s.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] However, early floating-gate memory required engineers to build a memory cell for each bit of data, which proved to be cumbersome, slow, and expensive, restricting floating-gate memory to niche applications in the 1970s, such as military equipment and the earliest experimental mobile phones.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Modern EEPROM based on Fowler-Nordheim tunnelling to erase data was invented by Bernward and patented by Siemens in 1974.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] It was further developed between 1976 and 1978 by Eliyahou Harari at Hughes Aircraft Company, as well as by George Perlegos and others at Intel.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Fujio Masuoka invented flash memory at Toshiba in 1980.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The improvement between EEPROM and flash is that flash is programmed in blocks while EEPROM is programmed in bytes.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] According to Toshiba, the name "flash" was suggested by Masuoka's colleague, Shōji Ariizumi, because the erasure process of the memory contents reminded him of the flash of a camera.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Masuoka and colleagues presented the invention of NOR flash in 1984, and then NAND flash at the *IEEE 1987 International Electron Devices Meeting* (IEDM) held in San Francisco.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Toshiba commercially launched NAND flash memory in 1987.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Intel Corporation introduced the first commercial NOR type flash chip in 1988.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NOR-based flash has long erase and write times, but provides full address and data buses, allowing random access to any memory location.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This makes it a suitable replacement for older read-only memory (ROM) chips, which are used to store program code that rarely needs to be updated, such as a computer's BIOS or the firmware of set-top boxes.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Its endurance may be from as little as 100 erase cycles for an on-chip flash memory, to a more typical 10,000 or 100,000 erase cycles, up to 1,000,000 erase cycles.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NOR-based flash was the basis of early flash-based removable media; CompactFlash was originally based on it, although later cards moved to less expensive NAND flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND flash has reduced erase and write times, and requires less chip area per cell, thus allowing greater storage density and lower cost per bit than NOR flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] However, the I/O interface of NAND flash does not provide a random-access external address bus.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Rather, data must be read on a block-wise basis, with typical block sizes of hundreds to thousands of bits.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This makes NAND flash unsuitable as a drop-in replacement for program ROM, since most microprocessors and microcontrollers require byte-level random access.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In this regard, NAND flash is similar to other secondary data storage devices, such as hard disks and optical media, and is thus highly suitable for use in mass-storage devices, such as memory cards and solid-state drives (SSD).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] For example, SSDs store data using multiple NAND flash memory chips.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The first NAND-based removable memory card format was SmartMedia, released in 1995.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Many others followed, including MultiMediaCard, Secure Digital, Memory Stick, and xD-Picture Card.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A new generation of memory card formats, including RS-MMC, miniSD and microSD, feature extremely small form factors.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] For example, the microSD card has an area of just over 1.5 cm2, with a thickness of less than 1 mm.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND flash has achieved significant levels of memory density as a result of several major technologies that were commercialized during the late 2000s to early 2010s.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NOR flash was the most common type of Flash memory sold until 2005, when NAND flash overtook NOR flash in sales.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Multi-level cell (MLC) technology stores more than one bit in each memory cell.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NEC demonstrated multi-level cell (MLC) technology in 1998, with an 80 Mb flash memory chip storing 2 bits per cell.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] STMicroelectronics also demonstrated MLC in 2000, with a 64 MB NOR flash memory chip.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In 2009, Toshiba and SanDisk introduced NAND flash chips with QLC technology storing 4 bits per cell and holding a capacity of 64 Gb.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Samsung Electronics introduced triple-level cell (TLC) technology storing 3-bits per cell, and began mass-producing NAND chips with TLC technology in 2010.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Charge trap flash (CTF) technology replaces the polysilicon floating gate, which is sandwiched between a blocking gate oxide above and a tunneling oxide below it, with an electrically insulating silicon nitride layer; the silicon nitride layer traps electrons.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In theory, CTF is less prone to electron leakage, providing improved data retention.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Because CTF replaces the polysilicon with an electrically insulating nitride, it allows for smaller cells and higher endurance (lower degradation or wear).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] However, electrons can become trapped and accumulate in the nitride, leading to degradation.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Leakage is exacerbated at high temperatures since electrons become more excited with increasing temperatures.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Degradation or wear of the oxides is the reason why flash memory has limited endurance.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Data retention goes down (the potential for data loss increases) with increasing degradation, since the oxides lose their electrically-insulating characteristics as they degrade.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The oxides must insulate against electrons to prevent them from leaking, which would cause data loss.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Oyama and Hiroki Shirai, described a type of flash memory with a charge-trap method.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In 1998, Boaz Eitan of Saifun Semiconductors (later acquired by Spansion) patented a flash memory technology named NROM that took advantage of a charge trapping layer to replace the conventional floating gate used in conventional flash memory designs.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In 2000, an Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) research team led by Richard M.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Ahmed and Jordanian engineer Sameer Haddad (who later joined Spansion) demonstrated a charge-trapping mechanism for NOR flash memory cells.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] CTF was later commercialized by AMD and Fujitsu in 2002.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] 3D V-NAND (vertical NAND) technology stacks NAND flash memory cells vertically within a chip using 3D charge trap flash (CTP) technology.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] 3D V-NAND technology was first announced by Toshiba in 2007, and the first device, with 24 layers, was commercialized by Samsung Electronics in 2013.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] 3D integrated circuit (3D IC) technology stacks integrated circuit (IC) chips vertically into a single 3D IC package.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Toshiba introduced 3D IC technology to NAND flash memory in April 2007, when they debuted a 16 GB eMMC compliant (product number THGAM0G7D8DBAI6, often abbreviated THGAM on consumer websites) embedded NAND flash memory package, which was manufactured with eight stacked 2 GB NAND flash chips.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In September 2007, Hynix Semiconductor (now SK Hynix) introduced 24-layer 3D IC technology, with a 16 GB flash memory package that was manufactured with 24 stacked NAND flash chips using a wafer bonding process.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Toshiba also used an eight-layer 3D IC for their 32 GB THGBM flash package and in 2008.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In 2010, Toshiba used a 16-layer 3D IC for their 128 GB THGBM2 flash package, which was manufactured with 16 stacked 8 GB chips.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In the 2010s, 3D ICs came into widespread commercial use for NAND flash memory in mobile devices.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In 2016, Micron and Intel introduced a technology known as CMOS Under the Array/CMOS Under Array (CUA), Core over Periphery (COP), Periphery Under Cell (PUA), or Xtacking, in which the control circuitry for the flash memory is placed under or above the flash memory cell array.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This has allowed for an increase in the number of planes or sections a flash memory chip has, increasing from two planes to four, without increasing the area dedicated to the control or periphery circuitry.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This increases the number of IO operations per flash chip or die, but it also introduces challenges when building capacitors for charge pumps used to write to the flash memory.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Some flash dies have as many as 6 planes.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] As of August 2017, microSD cards with a capacity up to 400 GB (400 billion bytes) were available.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Samsung combined 3D IC chip stacking with its 3D V-NAND and TLC technologies to manufacture its 512 GB KLUFG8R1EM flash memory package with eight stacked 64-layer V-NAND chips.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In 2019, Samsung produced a 1024 GB flash package, with eight stacked 96-layer V-NAND package and with QLC technology.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In 2025, researchers announced experimental success with a device having a 400-picosecond write time.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Flash memory stores information in an array of memory cells made from floating-gate transistors.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In single-level cell (SLC) devices, each cell stores only one bit of information.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Multi-level cell (MLC) devices, including triple-level cell (TLC) devices, can store more than one bit per cell.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The floating gate may be conductive (typically polysilicon in most kinds of flash memory) or non-conductive (as in SONOS flash memory).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In flash memory, each memory cell resembles a standard metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET) except that the transistor has two gates instead of one.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The cells can be seen as an electrical switch in which current flows between two terminals (source and drain) and is controlled by a floating gate (FG) and a control gate (CG).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The CG is similar to the gate in other MOS transistors, but below this is the FG, which is insulated all around by an oxide layer.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The FG is interposed between the CG and the MOSFET channel.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Because the FG is electrically isolated by its insulating layer, electrons placed on it are trapped.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] When the FG is charged with electrons, this charge screens the electric field from the CG, thus increasing the threshold voltage (VT) of the cell.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This means that the VT of the cell can be changed between the *uncharged FG threshold voltage* (VT1) and the higher *charged FG threshold voltage* (VT2) by changing the FG charge.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In order to read a value from the cell, an intermediate voltage (VI) between VT1 and VT2 is applied to the CG.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] If the channel conducts at VI, the FG must be uncharged (if it were charged, there would not be conduction because VI is less than VT2).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] If the channel does not conduct at the VI, it indicates that the FG is charged.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The binary value of the cell is sensed by determining whether there is current flowing through the transistor when VI is asserted on the CG.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In a multi-level cell device, which stores more than one bit per cell, the amount of current flow is sensed (rather than simply its presence or absence), in order to determine more precisely the level of charge on the FG.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Floating gate MOSFETs are so named because there is an electrically insulating tunnel oxide layer between the floating gate and the silicon, so the gate "floats" above the silicon.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The oxide keeps the electrons confined to the floating gate.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Degradation or wear (and the limited endurance of floating gate Flash memory) occurs due to the extremely high electric field (10 million volts per centimeter) experienced by the oxide.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This is why data retention goes down and the risk of data loss increases with increasing degradation.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The silicon oxide in a cell degrades with every erase operation.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The degradation increases the amount of negative charge in the cell over time due to trapped electrons in the oxide and negates some of the control gate voltage.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Over time, this also makes erasing the cell slower; to maintain the performance and reliability of the NAND chip, the cell must be retired from use.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Endurance also decreases with the number of bits in a cell.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] With more bits in a cell, the number of possible states (each represented by a different voltage level) in a cell increases and is more sensitive to the voltages used for programming.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The process of moving electrons from the control gate and into the floating gate is called Fowler–Nordheim tunneling, and it fundamentally changes the characteristics of the cell by increasing the MOSFET's threshold voltage.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This, in turn, changes the drain-source current that flows through the transistor for a given gate voltage, which is ultimately used to encode a binary value.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The Fowler-Nordheim tunneling effect is reversible, so electrons can be added to or removed from the floating gate, processes traditionally known as writing and erasing.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Despite the need for relatively high programming and erasing voltages, virtually all flash chips today require only a single supply voltage and produce the high voltages that are required using on-chip charge pumps.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Over half the energy used by a 1.8 V-NAND flash chip is lost in the charge pump itself.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In spacecraft and other high-radiation environments, the on-chip charge pump is the first part of the flash chip to fail, although flash memories will continue to work – in read-only mode – at much higher radiation levels.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In both NOR and NAND flash memories, the cells are arranged in a grid.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] We can think of the memory as consisting of "words" of a certain number of bits (or cells), with each word being confined to a particular column of the grid, and the bits being in different rows.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] All the bits of a particular word are linked by a wordline, a conductor connecting to the control gates of all the bits of that word.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] All the first bits of a certain number of adjacent words (columns) are linked by a bitline, as are all the second bits and so on.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The bitlines connect to one of the terminals (source or drain) of the cells.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] By manipulating the voltages on the wordlines one can read a certain bit by measuring the voltage on the corresponding bitline.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The way to do this depends on whether the memory chip is a NOR or a NAND flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In NOR flash, each cell has one end connected directly to ground, and the other end connected directly to a bit line.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This arrangement is called "NOR flash" because it acts like a NOR gate – if any of the word lines (connected to the CG of the cells) is brought high, the corresponding storage transistor may act to pull the output bit line low, but this depends on the charge in the floating gate.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Since several words are connected by the bit line, the output does not depend on only two (the bitline staying high if neither the first NOR the second wordline is high) but on all (the bitline remaining high if NONE of the wordlines is high).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] So to read a bit of a certain word, all the wordlines except that of the desired word are put low.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NOR flash continues to be the technology of choice for embedded applications requiring a discrete non-volatile memory device.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The low read latencies characteristic of NOR devices allow for both direct code execution and data storage in a single memory product.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A single-level NOR flash cell in its default state is logically equivalent to a binary "1" value, because current will flow through the channel under application of an appropriate voltage to the control gate, so that the bitline voltage is pulled down.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] To erase a NOR flash cell (resetting it to the "1" state), a large voltage *of the opposite polarity* is applied between the CG and source terminal, pulling the electrons off the FG through Fowler–Nordheim tunneling (FN tunneling).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This is known as Negative gate source erase.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Newer NOR memories can erase using negative gate channel erase, which biases the wordline on a NOR memory cell block and the P-well of the memory cell block to allow FN tunneling to be carried out, erasing the cell block.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Older memories used source erase, in which a high voltage was applied to the source and then electrons from the FG were moved to the source.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Modern NOR flash memory chips are divided into erase segments (often called blocks or sectors).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The erase operation can be performed only on a block-wise basis; all the cells in an erase segment must be erased together.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Programming of NOR cells, however, generally can be performed one byte or word at a time.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] To read the bit of a particular word, its wordline is put low and all the other wordlines are put high, and then the bitline will reflect the state of the floating gate of the desired cell.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] These groups are then connected via some additional transistors to a NOR-style bit line array in the same way that single transistors are linked in NOR flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Compared to NOR flash, replacing single transistors with serial-linked groups adds an extra level of addressing.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Whereas NOR flash might address memory by page then word, NAND flash might address it by page, word and bit.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Bit-level addressing suits bit-serial applications (such as hard disk emulation), which access only one bit at a time.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Execute-in-place applications, on the other hand, require every bit in a word to be accessed simultaneously.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In any case, both bit and word addressing modes are possible with either NOR or NAND flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] To read data, first the desired group is selected (in the same way that a single transistor is selected from a NOR array).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Next, most of the word lines are pulled up above VT2, while one of them is pulled up to VI.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The series group will conduct (and pull the bit line low) if the selected bit has not been programmed.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Despite the additional transistors, the reduction in ground wires and bit lines allows a denser layout and greater storage capacity per chip.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] (The ground wires and bit lines are actually much wider than the lines in the diagrams.) In addition, NAND flash is typically permitted to contain a certain number of faults (NOR flash, as is used for a BIOS ROM, is expected to be fault-free).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Manufacturers try to maximize the amount of usable storage by shrinking the size of the transistors or cells, however the industry can avoid this and achieve higher storage densities per die by using 3D NAND, which stacks cells on top of each other.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND flash cells are read by analysing their response to various voltages.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND flash uses tunnel injection for writing and tunnel release for erasing.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND flash memory forms the core of the removable USB storage devices known as USB flash drives, as well as most memory card formats and solid-state drives available today.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The hierarchical structure of NAND flash starts at a cell level which establishes strings, then pages, blocks, planes and ultimately a die.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A string is a series of connected NAND cells in which the source of one cell is connected to the drain of the next one.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Depending on the NAND technology, a string typically consists of 32 to 128 NAND cells.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Strings are organised into pages which are then organised into blocks in which each string is connected to a separate line called a bitline.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] All cells with the same position in the string are connected through the control gates by a wordline.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A plane contains a certain number of blocks that are connected through the same bitline.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A flash die consists of one or more planes, and the peripheral circuitry that is needed to perform all the read, write, and erase operations.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The architecture of NAND flash means that data can be read and programmed (written) in pages, typically between 4 KiB and 16 KiB in size, but can only be erased at the level of entire blocks consisting of multiple pages.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] When a block is erased, all the cells are logically set to 1.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Data can only be programmed in one pass to a page in a block that was erased.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The programming process is set one or more cells from 1 to 0.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Any cells that have been set to 0 by programming can only be reset to 1 by erasing the entire block.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This means that before new data can be programmed into a page that already contains data, the current contents of the page plus the new data must all be copied to a new, erased page.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] If a suitable erased page is available, the data can be written to it immediately.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] If no erased page is available, a block must be erased before copying the data to a page in that block.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The old page is then marked as invalid and is available for erasing and reuse.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This is different from operating system LBA view, for example, if operating system writes 1100 0011 to the flash storage device (such as SSD), the data actually written to the flash memory may be 0011 1100.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Vertical NAND (V-NAND) or 3D NAND memory stacks memory cells vertically and uses a charge trap flash architecture.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The vertical layers allow larger areal bit densities without requiring smaller individual cells.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] It is also sold under the trademark *BiCS Flash*, which is a trademark of Kioxia Corporation (formerly Toshiba Memory Corporation).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] 3D NAND was first announced by Toshiba in 2007.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] V-NAND was first commercially manufactured by Samsung Electronics in 2013.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] V-NAND uses a charge trap flash geometry (which was commercially introduced in 2002 by AMD and Fujitsu) that stores charge on an embedded silicon nitride film.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Such a film is more robust against point defects and can be made thicker to hold larger numbers of electrons.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] V-NAND wraps a planar charge trap cell into a cylindrical form.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] As of 2020, 3D NAND flash memories by Micron and Intel instead use floating gates, however, Micron 128 layer and above 3D NAND memories use a conventional charge trap structure, due to the dissolution of the partnership between Micron and Intel.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Charge trap 3D NAND flash is thinner than floating gate 3D NAND.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In floating gate 3D NAND, the memory cells are completely separated from one another, whereas in charge trap 3D NAND, vertical groups of memory cells share the same silicon nitride material.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] An individual memory cell is made up of one planar polysilicon layer containing a hole filled by multiple concentric vertical cylinders.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The hole's polysilicon surface acts as the gate electrode.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The outermost silicon dioxide cylinder acts as the gate dielectric, enclosing a silicon nitride cylinder that stores charge, in turn enclosing a silicon dioxide cylinder as the tunnel dielectric that surrounds a central rod of conducting polysilicon which acts as the conducting channel.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Memory cells in different vertical layers do not interfere with each other, as the charges cannot move vertically through the silicon nitride storage medium, and the electric fields associated with the gates are closely confined within each layer.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The vertical collection is electrically identical to the serial-linked groups in which conventional NAND flash memory is configured.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] There is also string stacking, which builds several 3D NAND memory arrays or "plugs" separately, but stacked together to create a product with a higher number of 3D NAND layers on a single die.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The misalignment between plugs is in the order of 30 to 10nm.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Growth of a group of V-NAND cells begins with an alternating stack of conducting (doped) polysilicon layers and insulating silicon dioxide layers.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The next step is to form a cylindrical hole through these layers.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In practice, a 128 Gbit V-NAND chip with 24 layers of memory cells requires about 2.9 billion such holes.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Next, the hole's inner surface receives multiple coatings, first silicon dioxide, then silicon nitride, then a second layer of silicon dioxide.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Finally, the hole is filled with conducting (doped) polysilicon.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] As of 2013, V-NAND flash architecture allows read and write operations twice as fast as conventional NAND and can last up to 10 times as long, while consuming 50 percent less power.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] They offer comparable physical bit density using 10-nm lithography but may be able to increase bit density by up to two orders of magnitude, given V-NAND's use of up to several hundred layers.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] As of 2020, V-NAND chips with 160 layers are under development by Samsung.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] As the number of layers increases, the capacity and endurance of flash memory may be increased.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The wafer cost of a 3D NAND is comparable with scaled down (32 nm or less) planar NAND flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] However, with planar NAND scaling stopping at 16 nm, the cost per bit reduction can continue by 3D NAND starting with 16 layers.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] However, due to the non-vertical sidewall of the hole etched through the layers; even a slight deviation leads to a minimum bit cost, i.e., minimum equivalent design rule (or maximum density), for a given number of layers; this minimum bit cost layer number decreases for smaller hole diameter.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] One limitation of flash memory is that it can be erased only a block at a time.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This generally sets all bits in the block to 1.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Starting with a freshly erased block, any location within that block can be programmed.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] However, once a bit has been set to 0, only by erasing the entire block can it be changed back to 1.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In other words, flash memory (specifically NOR flash) offers random-access read and programming operations but does not offer arbitrary random-access rewrite or erase operations.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A location can, however, be rewritten as long as the new value's 0 bits are a superset of the over-written values.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] For example, a nibble value may be erased to 1111, then written as 1110.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Successive writes to that nibble can change it to 1010, then 0010, and finally 0000.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Essentially, erasure sets all bits to 1, and programming can only clear bits to 0.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Some file systems designed for flash devices make use of this rewrite capability, for example YAFFS1, to represent sector metadata.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Other flash file systems, such as YAFFS2, never make use of this "rewrite" capability – they do a lot of extra work to meet a "write once rule".
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Although data structures in flash memory cannot be updated in completely general ways, this allows members to be "removed" by marking them as invalid.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This technique may need to be modified for multi-level cell devices, where one memory cell holds more than one bit.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Common flash devices such as USB flash drives and memory cards provide only a block-level interface, or flash translation layer (FTL), which writes to a different cell each time to wear-level the device.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This prevents incremental writing within a block; however, it does help the device from being prematurely worn out by intensive write patterns.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Data stored on flash cells is steadily lost due to electron detrapping.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The rate of loss increases exponentially as the absolute temperature increases.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] For example: For a 45 nm NOR flash, at 1000 hours, the threshold voltage (Vt) loss at 25°C is about half that at 90°C.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Another limitation is that flash memory has a finite number of program–erase cycles (typically written as P/E cycles).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Micron Technology and Sun Microsystems announced an SLC NAND flash memory chip rated for 1,000,000 P/E cycles on 17 December 2008.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The guaranteed cycle count may apply only to block zero (as is the case with TSOP NAND devices), or to all blocks (as in NOR).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This effect is mitigated in some chip firmware or file system drivers by counting the writes and dynamically remapping blocks in order to spread write operations between sectors; this technique is called wear leveling.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Another approach is to perform write verification and remapping to spare sectors in case of write failure, a technique called bad block management (BBM).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] For portable consumer devices, these wear out management techniques typically extend the life of the flash memory beyond the life of the device itself, and some data loss may be acceptable in these applications.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] For high-reliability data storage, however, it is not advisable to use flash memory that would have to go through a large number of programming cycles.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This limitation also exists for "read-only" applications such as thin clients and routers, which are programmed only once or at most a few times during their lifetimes, due to *read disturb* (see below).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The result was to be a chip that could be erased and rewritten over and over, even when it should theoretically break down.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] As promising as Macronix's breakthrough might have been for the mobile industry, however, there were no plans for a commercial product featuring this capability to be released any time in the near future.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The method used to read NAND flash memory can cause nearby cells in the same memory block to change over time (become programmed).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The threshold number of reads is generally in the hundreds of thousands of reads between intervening erase operations.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] If reading continually from one cell, that cell will not fail but rather one of the surrounding cells will on a subsequent read.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] To avoid the read disturb problem the flash controller will typically count the total number of reads to a block since the last erase.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] When the count exceeds a target limit, the affected block is copied over to a new block, erased, then released to the block pool.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The original block is as good as new after the erase.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] If the flash controller does not intervene in time, however, a **read disturb** error will occur with possible data loss if the errors are too numerous to correct with an error-correcting code.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Most flash ICs come in ball grid array (BGA) packages, and even the ones that do not are often mounted on a PCB next to other BGA packages.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] After PCB assembly, boards with BGA packages are often X-rayed to see if the balls are making proper connections to the proper pad, or if the BGA needs rework.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] These X-rays can erase programmed bits in a flash chip (convert programmed "0" bits into erased "1" bits).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Erased bits ("1" bits) are not affected by X-rays.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Some manufacturers are now making X-ray-proof SD and USB memory devices.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The low-level interface to flash memory chips differs from those of other memory types such as DRAM, ROM, and EEPROM, which support bit-alterability (both zero to one and one to zero) and random access via externally accessible address buses.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NOR memory has an external address bus for reading and programming.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] For NOR memory, reading and programming are random-access, and unlocking and erasing are block-wise.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] For NAND memory, reading and programming are page-wise, and unlocking and erasing are block-wise.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Reading from NOR flash is similar to reading from random-access memory, provided the address and data bus are mapped correctly.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Because of this, most microprocessors can use NOR flash memory as execute in place (XIP) memory, meaning that programs stored in NOR flash can be executed directly from the NOR flash without needing to be copied into RAM first.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NOR flash may be programmed in a random-access manner similar to reading.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Programming changes bits from a logical one to a zero.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Bits that are already zero are left unchanged.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Erasure must happen a block at a time, and resets all the bits in the erased block back to one.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Typical block sizes are 64, 128, or 256 KiB.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Bad block management is a relatively new feature in NOR chips.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] In older NOR devices not supporting bad block management, the software or device driver controlling the memory chip must correct for blocks that wear out, or the device will cease to work reliably.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The specific commands used to lock, unlock, program, or erase NOR memories differ for each manufacturer.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] To avoid needing unique driver software for every device made, special Common Flash Memory Interface (CFI) commands allow the device to identify itself and its critical operating parameters.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Besides its use as random-access ROM, NOR flash can also be used as a storage device, by taking advantage of random-access programming.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Some devices offer read-while-write functionality so that code continues to execute even while a program or erase operation is occurring in the background.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] For sequential data writes, NOR flash chips typically have slow write speeds, compared with NAND flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Typical NOR flash does not need an error correcting code.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND flash architecture was introduced by Toshiba in 1989.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] These memories are accessed much like block devices, such as hard disks.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Each block consists of a number of pages.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The pages are typically 512, 2,048, or 4,096 bytes in size.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Associated with each page are a few bytes (typically 1/32 of the data size) that can be used for storage of an error correcting code (ECC) checksum.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Modern NAND flash may have erase block size between 1 MiB to 128 MiB.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] While reading and programming is performed on a page basis, erasure can only be performed on a block basis.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Since changing a cell from 0 to 1 requires erasing an entire block instead of just modifying some pages, making changes to the data of a block may in reality be a read-erase-write (REW) or read-modify-erase-write (RMEW) process, where the new data is actually moved to another block.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND devices also require bad block management by the device driver software or by the flash memory controller chip.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Some SD cards, for example, include controller circuitry to perform bad block management and wear leveling.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] When a logical block is accessed by high-level software, it is mapped to a physical block by the device driver or controller.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A number of blocks on the flash chip may be set aside for storing mapping tables to deal with bad blocks, or the system may simply check each block at power-up to create a bad block map in RAM.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The overall memory capacity gradually shrinks as more blocks are marked as bad.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND relies on ECC to compensate for bits that may spontaneously fail during normal device operation.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A typical ECC will correct a one-bit error in each 2048 bits (256 bytes) using 22 bits of ECC, or a one-bit error in each 4096 bits (512 bytes) using 24 bits of ECC.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] If the ECC cannot correct the error during read, it may still detect the error.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] When doing erase or program operations, the device can detect blocks that fail to program or erase and mark them bad.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The data is then written to a different, good block, and the bad block map is updated.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Hamming codes are the most commonly used ECC for SLC NAND flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Reed–Solomon codes and BCH codes (Bose–Chaudhuri–Hocquenghem codes) are commonly used ECC for MLC NAND flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Some MLC NAND flash chips internally generate the appropriate BCH error correction codes.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Most NAND devices are shipped from the factory with some bad blocks.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] These are typically marked according to a specified bad block marking strategy.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] By allowing some bad blocks, manufacturers achieve far higher yields than would be possible if all blocks had to be verified to be good.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This significantly reduces NAND flash costs and only slightly decreases the storage capacity of the parts.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] When executing software from NAND memories, virtual memory strategies are often used: memory contents must first be paged or copied into memory-mapped RAM and executed there (leading to the common combination of NAND + RAM).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A memory management unit (MMU) in the system is helpful, but this can also be accomplished with overlays.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] For this reason, some systems will use a combination of NOR and NAND memories, where a smaller NOR memory is used as software ROM and a larger NAND memory is partitioned with a file system for use as a non-volatile data storage area.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND sacrifices the random-access and execute-in-place advantages of NOR.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] NAND is best suited to systems requiring high capacity data storage.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] It offers higher densities, larger capacities, and lower cost.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] It has faster erases, sequential writes, and sequential reads.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A group called the Open NAND Flash Interface Working Group (ONFI) has developed a standardized low-level interface for NAND flash chips.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This allows interoperability between conforming NAND devices from different vendors.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The ONFI specification version 1.0 was released on 28 December 2006.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The ONFI group is supported by major NAND flash manufacturers, including Hynix, Intel, Micron Technology, and Numonyx, as well as by major manufacturers of devices incorporating NAND flash chips.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] Two major flash device manufacturers, Toshiba and Samsung, have chosen to use an NAND flash interface of their own design known as Toggle Mode (and now Toggle).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] This interface isn't pin-to-pin compatible with the ONFI specification.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The result is that a product designed for one vendor's devices may not be able to use another vendor's devices.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] A group of vendors, including Intel, Dell, and Microsoft, formed a Non-Volatile Memory Host Controller Interface (NVMHCI) Working Group.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p01] The goal of the group is to provide standard software and hardware programming interfaces for nonvolatile memory subsystems, including the "flash cache" device connected to the PCI Express bus.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] NOR and NAND flash get their names from the structure of the interconnections between memory cells.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In NOR flash, cells are connected in parallel to the bit lines, allowing cells to be read and programmed individually.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The parallel connection of cells resembles the parallel connection of transistors in a CMOS NOR gate.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In NAND flash, cells are connected in series, resembling a CMOS NAND gate.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The series connections consume less space than parallel ones, reducing the cost of NAND flash.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] It does not, by itself, prevent NAND cells from being read and programmed individually.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Each NOR flash cell is larger than a NAND flash cell – 10 F2 vs 4 F2 – even when using exactly the same semiconductor device fabrication and so each transistor, contact, etc. is exactly the same size – because NOR flash cells require a separate metal contact for each cell.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Because of the series connection and removal of wordline contacts, a large grid of NAND flash memory cells will occupy perhaps only 60% of the area of equivalent NOR cells (assuming the same CMOS process resolution, for example, 130 nm, 90 nm, or 65 nm).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] NAND flash's designers realized that the area of a NAND chip, and thus the cost, could be further reduced by removing the external address and data bus circuitry.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Instead, external devices could communicate with NAND flash via sequential-accessed command and data registers, which would internally retrieve and output the necessary data.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] This design choice made random-access of NAND flash memory impossible, but the goal of NAND flash was to replace mechanical hard disks, not to replace ROMs.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The first GSM phones and many feature phones had NOR flash memory, from which processor instructions could be executed directly in an execute-in-place architecture and allowed for short boot times.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] With smartphones, NAND flash memory was adopted as it has larger storage capacities and lower costs, but causes longer boot times because instructions cannot be executed from it directly, and must be copied to RAM memory first before execution.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The write endurance of SLC floating-gate NOR flash is typically equal to or greater than that of NAND flash, while MLC NOR and NAND flash have similar endurance capabilities.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Examples of endurance cycle ratings listed in datasheets for NAND and NOR flash, as well as in storage devices using flash memory, are provided.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] However, by applying certain algorithms and design paradigms, such as wear leveling, flash over-provisioning and high-quality flash memory (such as pSLC and eTLC), the endurance of a storage system can be tuned to serve specific requirements.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In order to compute the longevity of the NAND flash, one must account for the size of the memory chip, the type of memory (e.g.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Industrial NAND and server NAND are in demand due to their capacity, longer endurance and reliability in sensitive environments.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] As the number of bits per cell increases, performance and life of NAND flash may degrade, increasing random read times to 100μs for TLC NAND which is 4 times the time required in SLC NAND, and twice the time required in MLC NAND, for random reads.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Because of the particular characteristics of flash memory, it is best used with either a controller to perform wear leveling and error correction or specifically designed flash file systems, which spread writes over the media and deal with the long erase times of NOR flash blocks.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The basic concept behind flash file systems is the following: when the flash store is to be updated, the file system will write a new copy of the changed data to a fresh block, remap the file pointers, then erase the old block later when it has time.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In practice, flash file systems are used only for memory technology devices (MTDs), which are embedded flash memories that do not have a controller.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Removable flash memory cards, SSDs, eMMC/eUFS chips and USB flash drives have built-in controllers to perform wear leveling and error correction so use of a specific flash file system may not add benefit.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Multiple chips are often arrayed or die stacked to achieve higher capacities for use in consumer electronic devices such as multimedia players or GPSs.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The capacity scaling (increase) of flash chips used to follow Moore's law because they are manufactured with many of the same integrated circuits techniques and equipment.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Since the introduction of 3D NAND, scaling is no longer necessarily associated with Moore's law since ever smaller transistors (cells) are no longer used.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Consumer flash storage devices typically are advertised with usable sizes expressed as a small integer power of two (2, 4, 8, etc.) and a conventional designation of megabytes (MB) or gigabytes (GB); e.g., 512 MB, 8 GB.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] This includes SSDs marketed as hard drive replacements, in accordance with traditional hard drives, which use decimal prefixes.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Thus, an SSD marked as "64 GB" is at least 64 × 10003 bytes (64 GB).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Most users will have slightly less capacity than this available for their files, due to the space taken by file system metadata and because some operating systems report SSD capacity using binary prefixes which are somewhat larger than conventional prefixes .
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The flash memory chips inside them are sized in strict binary multiples, but the actual total capacity of the chips is not usable at the drive interface.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] It is considerably larger than the advertised capacity in order to allow for distribution of writes (wear leveling), for sparing, for error correction codes, and for other metadata needed by the device's internal firmware.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In 2005, Toshiba and SanDisk developed a NAND flash chip capable of storing 1 GB of data using multi-level cell (MLC) technology, capable of storing two bits of data per cell.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In September 2005, Samsung Electronics announced that it had developed the world's first 2 GB chip.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In March 2006, Samsung announced flash hard drives with capacity of 4 GB, essentially the same order of magnitude as smaller laptop hard drives, and in September 2006, Samsung announced an 8 GB chip produced using a 40 nm manufacturing process.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In January 2008, SanDisk announced availability of their 16 GB MicroSDHC and 32 GB SDHC Plus cards.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] More recent flash drives (as of 2012) have much greater capacities, holding 64, 128, and 256 GB.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] A joint development at Intel and Micron will allow the production of 32-layer 3.5 terabyte (TB) NAND flash sticks and 10 TB standard-sized SSDs.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The device includes 5 packages of 16 × 48 GB TLC dies, using a floating gate cell design.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Flash chips continue to be manufactured with capacities under or around 1 MB (e.g. for BIOS-ROMs and embedded applications).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In July 2016, Samsung announced the 4 TB Samsung 850 EVO which utilizes their 256 Gbit 48-layer TLC 3D V-NAND.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In August 2016, Samsung announced a 32 TB 2.5-inch SAS SSD based on their 512 Gbit 64-layer TLC 3D V-NAND.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Further, Samsung expects to unveil SSDs with up to 100 TB of storage by 2020.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Flash memory devices are typically much faster at reading than writing.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Performance also depends on the quality of storage controllers, which become more critical when devices are partially full.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Even when the only change to manufacturing is die-shrink, the absence of an appropriate controller can result in degraded speeds.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Serial flash is a small, low-power flash memory that provides only serial access to the data - rather than addressing individual bytes, the user reads or writes large contiguous groups of bytes in the address space serially.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Serial Peripheral Interface Bus (SPI) is a typical protocol for accessing the device.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] When incorporated into an embedded system, serial flash requires fewer wires on the PCB than parallel flash memories, since it transmits and receives data one bit at a time.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] This may permit a reduction in board space, power consumption, and total system cost.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The first type is characterized by small blocks and one internal SRAM block buffer allowing a complete block to be read to the buffer, partially modified, and then written back (for example, the Atmel AT45 *DataFlash* or the Micron Technology Page Erase NOR Flash).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The second type has larger sectors where the smallest sectors typically found in this type of SPI flash are 4 KB, but they can be as large as 64 KB.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Since this type of SPI flash lacks an internal SRAM buffer, the complete block must be read out and modified before being written back, making it slow to manage.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] However, the second type is cheaper than the first and is therefore a good choice when the application is code shadowing.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The two types are not easily exchangeable, since they do not have the same pinout, and the command sets are incompatible.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Most FPGAs are based on SRAM configuration cells and require an external configuration device, often a serial flash chip, to reload the configuration bitstream every power cycle.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] With the increasing speed of modern CPUs, parallel flash devices are often much slower than the memory bus of the computer they are connected to.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Conversely, modern SRAM offers access times below 10 ns, while DDR2 SDRAM offers access times below 20 ns.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Because of this, it is often desirable to shadow code stored in flash into RAM; that is, the code is copied from flash into RAM before execution, so that the CPU may access it at full speed.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Device firmware may be stored in a serial flash chip, and then copied into SDRAM or SRAM when the device is powered-up.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Using an external serial flash device rather than on-chip flash removes the need for significant process compromise (a manufacturing process that is good for high-speed logic is generally not good for flash and vice versa).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Once it is decided to read the firmware in as one big block it is common to add compression to allow a smaller flash chip to be used.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Since 2005, many devices use serial NOR flash to deprecate parallel NOR flash for firmware storage.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Typical applications for serial NOR flash include storing firmware for hard drives, BIOS, Option ROM of expansion cards, DSL modems, etc.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] One more recent application for flash memory is as a replacement for hard disks.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Flash memory does not have the mechanical limitations and latencies of hard drives, so a solid-state drive (SSD) is attractive in terms of speed, noise, power consumption, and reliability.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Flash drives are gaining traction as mobile device secondary storage devices; they are also used as substitutes for hard drives in high-performance desktop computers and some servers with RAID and SAN architectures.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] There remain some aspects of flash-based SSDs that make them unattractive.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The cost per gigabyte of flash memory remains significantly higher than that of hard disks.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Also, flash memory has a finite number of P/E (*program/erase*) cycles, but this seems to be currently under control since warranties on flash-based SSDs are approaching those of current hard drives.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In addition, deleted files on SSDs can remain for an indefinite period of time before being overwritten by fresh data; erasure or shred techniques or software that work well on magnetic hard disk drives have no effect on SSDs, compromising security and forensic examination.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] However, due to the so-called *TRIM* command employed by most solid state drives, which marks the logical block addresses occupied by the deleted file as unused to enable garbage collection, data recovery software is not able to restore files deleted from such.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] For relational databases or other systems that require ACID transactions, even a modest amount of flash storage can offer vast speedups over arrays of disk drives.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In May 2006, Samsung Electronics announced two flash-memory based PCs, the Q1-SSD and Q30-SSD were expected to become available in June 2006, both of which used 32 GB SSDs, and were at least initially available only in South Korea.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The Q1-SSD and Q30-SSD launch was delayed and finally was shipped in late August 2006.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The first flash-memory based PC to become available was the Sony Vaio UX90, announced for pre-order on 27 June 2006 and began to be shipped in Japan on 3 July 2006 with a 16 GB flash memory hard drive.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In late September 2006 Sony upgraded the flash-memory in the Vaio UX90 to 32 GB.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] A solid-state drive was offered as an option with the first MacBook Air introduced in 2008, and from 2010 onwards, all models were shipped with an SSD.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Starting in late 2011, as part of Intel's Ultrabook initiative, an increasing number of ultra-thin laptops are being shipped with SSDs standard.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] On smartphones, the NAND flash products are used as file storage device, for example, eMMC and eUFS.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] As of 2012, there are attempts to use flash memory as the main computer memory, DRAM.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Floating-gate transistors in the flash storage device hold charge which represents data.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] This charge gradually leaks over time, leading to an accumulation of logical errors, also known as "bit rot" or "bit fading".
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] It is unclear how long data on flash memory will persist under archival conditions (i.e., benign temperature and humidity with infrequent access with or without prophylactic rewrite).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Datasheets of Atmel's flash-based "ATmega" microcontrollers typically promise retention times of 20 years at 85 °C (185 °F) and 100 years at 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The retention span varies among types and models of flash storage.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] When supplied with power and idle, the charge of the transistors holding the data is routinely refreshed by the firmware of the flash storage.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The ability to retain data varies among flash storage devices due to differences in firmware, data redundancy, and error correction algorithms.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] An article from CMU in 2015 states "Today's flash devices, which do not require flash refresh, have a typical retention age of 1 year at room temperature." And that retention time decreases exponentially with increasing temperature.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The phenomenon can be modeled by the Arrhenius equation.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Some FPGAs are based on flash configuration cells that are used directly as (programmable) switches to connect internal elements together, using the same kind of floating-gate transistor as the flash data storage cells in data storage devices.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] One source states that, in 2008, the flash memory industry includes about US$9.1 billion in production and sales.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Other sources put the flash memory market at a size of more than US$20 billion in 2006, accounting for more than eight percent of the overall semiconductor market and more than 34 percent of the total semiconductor memory market.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In 2012, the market was estimated at $26.8 billion.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] It can take up to 10 weeks to produce a flash memory chip.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The following were the largest NAND flash memory manufacturers, as of the third quarter of 2025.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Notes: Samsung remains the largest NAND flash memory manufacturer as of Q3 2025.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Kioxia spun out and got renamed of Toshiba in 2018/2019.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] SK Hynix acquired Intel's NAND business at the end of 2021.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] In addition to individual flash memory chips, flash memory is also embedded in microcontroller (MCU) chips and system-on-chip (SoC) devices.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Flash memory is embedded in ARM chips, which have sold 150 billion units worldwide as of 2019, and in programmable system-on-chip (PSoC) devices, which have sold 1.1 billion units as of 2012.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] This adds up to at least 151.1 billion MCU and SoC chips with embedded flash memory, in addition to the 45.4 billion known individual flash chip sales as of 2015, totalling at least 196.5 billion chips containing flash memory.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Due to its relatively simple structure and high demand for higher capacity, NAND flash memory is the most aggressively scaled technology among electronic devices.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The heavy competition among the top few manufacturers only adds to the aggressiveness in shrinking the floating-gate MOSFET design rule or process technology node.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] While the expected shrink timeline is a factor of two every three years per the original version of Moore's law, this has recently been accelerated in the case of NAND flash to a factor of two every two years.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] As the MOSFET feature size of flash memory cells reaches the 15–16 nm minimum limit, further flash density increases will be driven by TLC (3 bits/cell) combined with vertical stacking of NAND memory planes.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] The decrease in endurance and increase in uncorrectable bit error rates that accompany feature size shrinking can be compensated by improved error correction mechanisms.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Even with these advances, it may be impossible to economically scale flash to smaller and smaller dimensions as the number of electron holding capacity reduces.
[src:embedded-systems/flash-memory-p02] Many promising new technologies (such as FeRAM, MRAM, PMC, PCM, ReRAM, and others) are under investigation and development as possible more scalable replacements for flash.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] There is no standard for in-system programming protocols for programming microcontroller devices.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Almost all manufacturers of microcontrollers support ISP, but all have implemented their own protocols, which often differ even for various devices from the same manufacturer.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Up to 4 pins may be required for implementing a JTAG standard interface.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] In general, modern protocols try to keep the number of pins used low, typically to 2 pins.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Some ISP interfaces manage to achieve the same with just a single pin.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Newer ATtiny microcontrollers with UPDI can even reuse that programming pin also as a general-purpose input/output.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The primary advantage of in-system programming is that it allows manufacturers of electronic devices to integrate programming and testing into a single production phase, and save money, rather than requiring a separate programming stage prior to assembling the system.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] This may allow manufacturers to program the chips in their own system's production line instead of buying pre-programmed chips from a manufacturer or distributor, making it feasible to apply code or design changes in the middle of a production run.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The other advantage is that production can always use the latest firmware, and new features as well as bug fixes can be implemented and put into production without the delay occurring when using pre-programmed microcontrollers.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Microcontrollers are typically soldered directly to a printed circuit board and usually do not have the circuitry or space for a large external programming cable to another computer.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Typically, chips supporting ISP have internal circuitry to generate any necessary programming voltage from the system's normal supply voltage, and communicate with the programmer via a serial protocol.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Most programmable logic devices use a variant of the JTAG protocol for ISP, in order to facilitate easier integration with automated testing procedures.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Other devices usually use proprietary protocols or protocols defined by older standards.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Starting from the early 1990s, an important technological evolution in the architecture of the microcontrollers was witnessed.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] At first, they were realized in two possible solutions: with one-time programmable (OTP) or with EPROM memories.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] For EPROM, a memory-erasing process requires the chip to be exposed to ultraviolet light through a specific window above the package.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] In 1993 Microchip Technology introduced the first microcontroller with EEPROM memory: the PIC16C84.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] EEPROM memories can be electrically erased.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] This feature allowed to lower the realization costs by removing the erasing window above the package and initiate in-system programming technology.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] With ISP flashing process can be performed directly on the board at the end of the production process.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] This evolution gave the possibility to unify the programming and functional test phase and in production environments and to start the preliminary production of the boards even if the firmware development has not yet been completed.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] This way it was possible to correct bugs or to make changes at a later time.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] In the same year, Atmel developed the first microcontroller with flash memory, easier and faster to program and with much longer life cycle compared to EEPROM memories.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Microcontrollers that support ISP are usually provided with pins used by the serial communication peripheral to interface with the programmer, a flash/EEPROM memory and the circuitry used to supply the voltage necessary to program the microcontroller.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The communication peripheral is in turn connected to a programming peripheral which provides commands to operate on the flash or EEPROM memory.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] When designing electronic boards for ISP programming, it’s necessary to take into account some guidelines to have a programming phase as reliable as possible.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Some microcontrollers with a low number of pins share the programming lines with the I/O lines.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] This can be a problem if the necessary precautions are not taken into account in the design of the board; the device can suffer the damage of the I/O components during the programming.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Moreover, it’s important to connect the ISP lines to high impedance circuitry both to avoid a damage of the components by the programmer and because the microcontroller often cannot supply enough current to pilot the line.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Many microcontrollers need a dedicated reset line to enter in the programming mode.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] It is necessary to pay attention to current supplied for line driving and to check for presence of watchdogs connected to the reset line that can generate an unwanted reset and, so, to lead a programming failure.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Moreover, some microcontrollers need a higher voltage to enter in Programming Mode and, hence, it’s necessary to check that this value it’s not attenuated and that this voltage is not forwarded to others components on the board.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] In-system programming takes place during the final stage of production of a product.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] In the first method, a connector is manually connected to the programmer.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] This solution expects the human participation to the programming process that has to connect the programmer to the electronic board with the cable.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Hence, this solution is meant for low production volumes.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The second method uses test points on the board.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] These are specific areas placed on the printed board, or PCB, that are electrically connected to some of the electronic components on the board.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Test points are used to perform functional tests for components mounted on board and, since they are connected directly to some microcontroller pins, they are very effective for ISP.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] For medium and high production volumes using test points is the best solution since it allows to integrate the programming phase in an assembly line.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] In production lines, boards are placed on a bed of nails called a fixture.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The latter are integrated, based on the production volumes, in semiautomatic or automatic test systems called automatic test equipment (ATE).
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Fixtures are specifically designed for each board - or at most for few models similar to the board they were designed for – therefore these are interchangeable in the system environment where they are integrated.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The test system, once the board and the fixture are placed in position, has a mechanism to put in contact the needles of the fixture with the test points on the board to test.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The system it’s connected to, or has directly integrated inside, an ISP programmer.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] This one has to program the device or devices mounted on the board: for example, a microcontroller and/or a serial memory.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] For most Microchip microcontrollers, ICSP programming is performed using two pins, clock (PGC) and data (PGD), while a high voltage (12 V) is present on the Vpp/MCLR pin.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Low voltage programming (5 V or 3.3 V) dispenses with the high voltage, but reserves exclusive use of an I/O pin.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] However, for newer microcontrollers, specifically PIC18F6XJXX/8XJXX microcontrollers families from Microchip Technology, entering into ICSP modes is a bit different.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] A 32-bit key sequence is presented on PGD.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] A separate piece of hardware, called a programmer is required to connect to an I/O port of a PC on one side and to the PIC on the other side.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] **Serial port** (COM port) - At one time the most popular method.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Serial ports usually lack adequate circuit programming supply voltage.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Most computers and laptops newer than 2010 lack support for this port.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] **Socket** (in or out of circuit) - the CPU must be either removed from circuit board, or a clamp must be attached to the chip-making access an issue.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] **USB cable** - Small and light weight, has support for voltage source and most computers have extra ports available.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The distance between the circuit to be programmed and the computer is limited by the length of USB cable - it must usually be less than 180 cm.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] This can make programming devices deep in machinery or cabinets a problem.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] ICSP programmers have many advantages, with size, computer port availability, and power source being major features.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Due to variations in the interconnect scheme and the target circuit surrounding a micro-controller, there is no programmer that works with ***all*** possible target circuits or interconnects.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Microchip Technology provides a detailed ICSP programming guide Many sites provide programming and circuit examples.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] PICs are programmed using five signals (a sixth pin 'aux' is provided but not used).
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The data is transferred using a two-wire synchronous serial scheme, three more wires provide programming and chip power.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The clock signal is always controlled by the programmer.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] Microchip supports an industry standard for using RJ11 sockets with an ICSP programmer.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The illustration represents information provided in their data sheets.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The PIC data sheets show an inverted socket and do not provide a pictorial view of pinouts so it is unclear what side of the socket Pin 1 is located on.
[src:embedded-systems/in-system-programming] The illustration provided here is **untested** but uses the phone industry standard pinout (the RJ11 plug/socket was originally developed for wired desktop phones).
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In computer systems programming, an **interrupt handler**, also known as an **interrupt service routine** (**ISR**), is a special block of code associated with a specific interrupt condition.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Interrupt handlers are initiated by hardware interrupts, software interrupt instructions, or software exceptions, and are used for implementing device drivers or transitions between protected modes of operation, such as system calls.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] The traditional form of interrupt handler is the hardware interrupt handler.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Hardware interrupts arise from an electrical trigger.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] The interrupt service routine must then save any registers it may change.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In general, hardware interrupts and their handlers are used to handle high-priority conditions that require the interruption of the current code the processor is executing.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] It is convenient for software to be able to trigger the same mechanism: a software interrupt.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Rather than using a hard-coded interrupt dispatch table at the hardware level, software interrupts are often implemented at the operating system level as a form of callback function.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Interrupt handlers have a multitude of functions, which vary based on what triggered the interrupt and the speed at which the interrupt handler completes its task.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] For example, pressing a key on a computer keyboard, or moving the mouse, triggers interrupts that call interrupt handlers which read the key, or the mouse's position, and copy the associated information into the computer's memory.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] An interrupt handler is a low-level counterpart of event handlers.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] During the execution of an interrupt service routine, it is possible for another interrupt to occur.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] How this second interrupt is handled is dependent on the hardware.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In general, a developer will decide whether or not to let the current ISR be interrupted to handle a higher priority interrupt.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] If so, the current program counter (and often flags) will be saved to the stack before the address of the higher priority ISR is written to the program counter.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] The higher priority interrupt service routine must then save any registers it may alter.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Upon completion of the higher priority ISR, the address and state from the lower priority ISR will be popped from the stack and execution of the lower priority ISR will continue.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Unlike other event handlers, interrupt handlers are expected to set interrupt flags to appropriate values as part of their core functionality.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Even in a CPU which supports nested interrupts, a handler is often reached with all interrupts globally masked by a CPU hardware operation.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In this architecture, an interrupt handler would normally save the smallest amount of context necessary, and then reset the global interrupt disable flag at the first opportunity, to permit higher priority interrupts to interrupt the current handler.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] It is also important for the interrupt handler to quell the current interrupt source by some method (often toggling a flag bit of some kind in a peripheral register) so that the current interrupt isn't immediately repeated on handler exit, resulting in an infinite loop.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Exiting an interrupt handler with the interrupt system in exactly the right state under every eventuality can sometimes be an arduous and exacting task, and its mishandling is the source of many serious bugs, of the kind that halt the system completely.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] These bugs are sometimes intermittent, with the mishandled edge case not occurring for weeks or months of continuous operation.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Formal validation of interrupt handlers is tremendously difficult, while testing typically identifies only the most frequent failure modes, thus subtle, intermittent bugs in interrupt handlers often ship to end customers.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In a modern operating system, upon entry the execution context of a hardware interrupt handler is subtle.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] However, unlike the interrupted process, the interrupt is usually elevated by a hard-coded CPU mechanism to a privilege level high enough to access hardware resources directly.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In a low-level microcontroller, the chip might lack protection modes or lack a memory management unit (MMU).
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In these chips, the execution context of an interrupt handler will be essentially the same as the interrupted program, which typically runs on a small stack of fixed size (memory resources have traditionally been extremely scant at the low end).
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Nested interrupts are often provided, which exacerbates stack usage.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] A primary constraint on the interrupt handler in this programming endeavour is to not exceed the available stack in the worst-case condition, requiring the programmer to reason globally about the stack space requirement of every implemented interrupt handler and application task.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] When allocated stack space is exceeded (a condition known as a stack overflow), this is not normally detected in hardware by chips of this class.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] If the stack is exceeded into another writable memory area, the handler will typically work as expected, but the application will fail later (sometimes much later) due to the handler's side effect of memory corruption.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] If the stack is exceeded into a non-writable (or protected) memory area, the failure will usually occur inside the handler itself (generally the easier case to later debug).
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In the writable case, one can implement a sentinel stack guard—a fixed value right beyond the end of the legal stack whose value *can* be overwritten, but never will be if the system operates correctly.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] It is common to regularly observe corruption of the stack guard with some kind of watch dog mechanism.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] This will catch the majority of stack overflow conditions at a point in time close to the offending operation.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In a multitasking system, each thread of execution will typically have its own stack.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] If no special system stack is provided for interrupts, interrupts will consume stack space from whatever thread of execution is interrupted.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] These designs usually contain an MMU, and the user stacks are usually configured such that stack overflow is trapped by the MMU, either as a system error (for debugging) or to remap memory to extend the space available.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Memory resources at this level of microcontroller are typically far less constrained, so that stacks can be allocated with a generous safety margin.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In systems supporting high thread counts, it is better if the hardware interrupt mechanism switches the stack to a special system stack, so that none of the thread stacks need account for worst-case nested interrupt usage.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Tiny CPUs as far back as the 8-bit Motorola 6809 from 1978 have provided separate system and user stack pointers.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] For many reasons, it is highly desired that the interrupt handler execute as briefly as possible, and it is highly discouraged (or forbidden) for a hardware interrupt to invoke potentially blocking system calls.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In a system with multiple execution cores, considerations of reentrancy are also paramount.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] If the system provides for hardware DMA, concurrency issues can arise even with only a single CPU core.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] A modern practice has evolved to divide hardware interrupt handlers into front-half and back-half elements.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In several operating systems‍—‌Linux, Unix, macOS, Microsoft Windows, z/OS, DESQview and some other operating systems used in the past‍—‌interrupt handlers are divided into two parts: the **First-Level Interrupt Handler** (**FLIH**) and the **Second-Level Interrupt Handlers** (**SLIH**).
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] FLIHs are also known as *hard interrupt handlers* or *fast interrupt handlers*, and SLIHs are also known as *slow/soft interrupt handlers*, or Deferred Procedure Calls in Windows.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] A FLIH implements at minimum platform-specific interrupt handling similar to *interrupt routines*.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In response to an interrupt, there is a context switch, and the code for the interrupt is executed.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] The job of a FLIH is to quickly service the interrupt, or to record platform-specific critical information which is only available at the time of the interrupt, and schedule the execution of a SLIH for further long-lived interrupt handling.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] FLIHs cause jitter in process execution.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Reducing the jitter is most important for real-time operating systems, since they must maintain a guarantee that execution of specific code will complete within an agreed amount of time.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] To reduce jitter and to reduce the potential for losing data from masked interrupts, programmers attempt to minimize the execution time of a FLIH, moving as much as possible to the SLIH.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] With the speed of modern computers, FLIHs may implement all device and platform-dependent handling, and use a SLIH for further platform-independent long-lived handling.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] FLIHs which service hardware typically mask their associated interrupt (or keep it masked as the case may be) until they complete their execution.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] An (unusual) FLIH which unmasks its associated interrupt before it completes is called a reentrant interrupt handler.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] Reentrant interrupt handlers might cause a stack overflow from multiple preemptions by the same interrupt vector, and so they are usually avoided.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In a priority interrupt system, the FLIH also (briefly) masks other interrupts of equal or lesser priority.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] A SLIH completes long interrupt processing tasks similarly to a process.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] SLIHs either have a dedicated kernel thread for each handler, or are executed by a pool of kernel worker threads.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] These threads sit on a run queue in the operating system until processor time is available for them to perform processing for the interrupt.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] SLIHs may have a long-lived execution time, and thus are typically scheduled similarly to threads and processes.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] In Linux, FLIHs are called *upper half*, and SLIHs are called *lower half* or *bottom half*.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt-handler] This is different from naming used in other Unix-like systems, where both are a part of *bottom half*.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] In digital computers, an **interrupt** is a request for the processor to *interrupt* currently executing code (when permitted), so that the event can be processed in a timely manner.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] If the request is accepted, the processor will suspend its current activities, save its state, and execute a function called an *interrupt handler* (or an *interrupt service routine*, ISR) to deal with the event.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] This interruption is often temporary, allowing the software to resume normal activities after the interrupt handler finishes, although the interrupt could instead indicate a fatal error.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Interrupts are commonly used by hardware devices to indicate electronic or physical state changes that require time-sensitive attention.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Interrupts are also commonly used to implement computer multitasking and system calls, especially in real-time computing.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Systems that use interrupts in these ways are said to be interrupt-driven.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Hardware interrupts were introduced as an optimization, eliminating unproductive waiting time in polling loops, waiting for external events.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] The first system to use this approach was the DYSEAC, completed in 1954, although earlier systems provided error trap functions.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] The UNIVAC 1103A computer is generally credited with the earliest use of interrupts in 1953.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Earlier, on the UNIVAC I (1951) "Arithmetic overflow either triggered the execution of a two-instruction fix-up routine at address 0, or, at the programmer's option, caused the computer to stop." The IBM 650 (1954) incorporated the first occurrence of interrupt masking.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] The National Bureau of Standards DYSEAC (1954) was the first to use interrupts for I/O.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] The IBM 704 was the first to use interrupts for debugging, with a "transfer trap", which could invoke a special routine when a branch instruction was encountered.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] The MIT Lincoln Laboratory TX-2 system (1957) was the first to provide multiple levels of priority interrupts.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Interrupt signals may be issued in response to hardware or software events.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] These are classified as **hardware interrupts** or **software interrupts**, respectively.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] For any particular processor, the number of interrupt types is limited by the architecture.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Such external devices may be part of the computer (e.g., disk controller) or they may be external peripherals.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] For example, pressing a keyboard key or moving a mouse plugged into a PS/2 port triggers hardware interrupts that cause the processor to read the keystroke or mouse position.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Hardware interrupts can arrive asynchronously with respect to the processor clock, and at any time during instruction execution.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Consequently, all incoming hardware interrupt signals are conditioned by synchronizing them to the processor clock, and acted upon only at instruction execution boundaries.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] In many systems, each device is associated with a particular IRQ signal.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] This makes it possible to quickly determine which hardware device is requesting service, and to expedite servicing of that device.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] On some older systems, such as the 1964 CDC 3600, all interrupts went to the same location, and the OS used a specialized instruction to determine the highest-priority outstanding unmasked interrupt.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] On contemporary systems, there is generally a distinct interrupt routine for each type of interrupt (or for each interrupt source), often implemented as one or more interrupt vector tables.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] To *mask* an interrupt is to disable it, so it is deferred or ignored by the processor, while to *unmask* an interrupt is to enable it.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Processors typically have an internal *interrupt mask* register, which allows selective enabling (and disabling) of hardware interrupts.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Each interrupt signal is associated with a bit in the mask register.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] On some systems, the interrupt is enabled when the bit is set, and disabled when the bit is clear.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] On others, the reverse is true, and a set bit disables the interrupt.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] When the interrupt is disabled, the associated interrupt signal may be ignored by the processor, or it may remain pending.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Signals which are affected by the mask are called *maskable interrupts*.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Some interrupt signals are not affected by the interrupt mask and therefore cannot be disabled; these are called *non-maskable interrupts* (NMIs).
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] These indicate high-priority events which cannot be ignored under any circumstances, such as the timeout signal from a watchdog timer.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] With regard to SPARC, the Non-Maskable Interrupt (NMI), despite having the highest priority among interrupts, can be prevented from occurring through the use of an interrupt mask.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] One failure mode is when the hardware does not generate the expected interrupt for a change in state, causing the operating system to wait indefinitely.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Depending on the details, the failure might affect only a single process or might have global impact.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Some operating systems have code specifically to deal with this.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] As an example, IBM Operating System/360 (OS/360) relies on a not-ready to ready device-end interrupt when a tape has been mounted on a tape drive, and will not read the tape label until that interrupt occurs or is simulated.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] IBM added code in OS/360 so that the VARY ONLINE command will simulate a device end interrupt on the target device.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] A *spurious interrupt* is a hardware interrupt for which no source can be found.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] The term "phantom interrupt" or "ghost interrupt" may also be used to describe this phenomenon.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Spurious interrupts tend to be a problem with a wired-OR interrupt circuit attached to a level-sensitive processor input.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] Such interrupts may be difficult to identify when a system misbehaves.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] In a wired-OR circuit, parasitic capacitance charging/discharging through the interrupt line's bias resistor will cause a small delay before the processor recognizes that the interrupt source has been cleared.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] If the interrupting device is cleared too late in the interrupt service routine (ISR), there will not be enough time for the interrupt circuit to return to the quiescent state before the current instance of the ISR terminates.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] The result is the processor will think another interrupt is pending, since the voltage at its interrupt request input will be not high or low enough to establish an unambiguous internal logic 1 or logic 0.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] The apparent interrupt will have no identifiable source, hence the "spurious" moniker.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] A spurious interrupt may also be the result of electrical anomalies due to faulty circuit design, high noise levels, crosstalk, timing issues, or more rarely, device errata.
[src:embedded-systems/interrupt] A spurious interrupt may result in system deadlock or other undefined operation if the ISR does not account for the possibility of such an interrupt occurring.
